v=SoFGu2arg88 |title=Flacco on Ravens Victory |via=YouTube |date=January 10, 2009 |accessdate=March 4, 2012}}</ref>\n* Second-most combined regular and postseason wins in first three years as a quarterback: 36 (tied with [[Dan Marino]])<ref>{{citation|last=Drovetto |first=Tony |url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/articles/article-1/Where-does-Russell-Wilson-rank-among-the-NFLs-final-four-QBs/ab2ce2f0-3f8d-4b9a-8fc0-adfe24c9125c |title=where does russel wilson rank among NFL final 4 QB's |publisher=seahawks.com |date=January 12, 2015 |accessdate=January 16, 2015}}</ref>\n* First quarterback to start and win a playoff game in each of his first five seasons (Russell Wilson tied record)<ref name=isnttop5>{{cite news|last=Banks |first=Don |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/nfl/news/20130106/nfl-playoffs-wild-card-snap-judgments/?sct=uk_t12_a2 |title=Wild Card Snap Judgments |work=Sports Illustrated  |date=January 6, 2013 |accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n* Most touchdowns in a postseason: 11 (tied with [[Joe Montana]] and [[Kurt Warner]])<ref name=Klemko/>\n* Most touchdowns without an interception in a postseason: 11 (tied with Joe Montana)<ref name=Barnwell/>\n* First quarterback to have a passer rating over 100 in all four games of a single postseason<ref name=Byrne/>\n* [[Most consecutive games with a touchdown pass (NFL)#All-time consecutive playoff games with at least two touchdown passes|Most consecutive playoff games with at least two passing touchdowns]]: 8\n* [[Most consecutive games with a touchdown pass (NFL)#All-time consecutive road playoff games with at least one touchdown pass|Most consecutive road playoff games with at least one passing touchdown]]: 7 (tied with [[Donovan McNabb]] and [[Brett Favre]])\n* [[Most consecutive games with a touchdown pass (NFL)#All-time consecutive road playoff games with at least two touchdown passes|Most consecutive road playoff games with at least two passing touchdowns]]: 5\n* Fastest quarterback to record five touchdowns in a game: 16:03<ref name=\"Chase\">{{Cite web |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/10/joe-flacco-baltimore-ravens-5-touchdowns-tampa-bay-buccaneers |title=Joe Flacco threw five TDs faster than any QB in modern NFL history |last=Chase |first=Chris |date=October 12, 2014 |website=USA Today |access-date=October 13, 2014}}</ref>\n* Most road playoff wins for a quarterback: 7 <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-flacco-is-the-king-of-the-nfl-playoffs-1420414837 |title=Joe Flacco Is the King of the NFL Playoffs |last=Salfino |first=Michael |date=January 4, 2015 |website=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Ravens franchise records===\n<!---DON'T ADD UNSOURCED RECORDS --->\n{{See also|Baltimore Ravens#Team records|l1=All Ravens franchise records}}\n* Most career passing yards \u2013 32,639<ref name=profbref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rav/ |title=Baltimore Ravens Team Encyclopedia |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n* Most career pass completions \u2013 2,915<ref name=profbref />\n* Most career pass attempts \u2013 4,742<ref name=profbref />\n* Most career passing touchdowns \u2013 182<ref name=profbref />\n* Most regular-season wins \u2013 84<ref name=profbref />\n* Most postseason wins \u2013 10<ref name=profbref />\n* Most consecutive pass completions: 21 vs. [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] on September 25, 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2016/09/25/joe-flacco-ravens-franchise-record-21-straight-completions/ |title=Joe Flacco Breaks Ravens Franchise Record With 21 Straight Completions |date=September 25, 2016 |website=CBS - Baltimore |language=en-US |access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* Most 300+ passing-yard games, career \u2013 32<ref name=profbref />\n* Most 300+ passing-yard games, season \u2013 6 (2012)<ref name=profbref />\n* Most 300+ passing-yard games, playoffs \u2013 2 <ref name=profbref />\n* Highest completion percentage in a single season \u2013 64.9% (2016) (in 16 starts)<ref name=profbref />\n* Highest career quarterback rating \u2013 84.6<ref name=profbref />\n* Most times sacked in a career for a starting quarterback\u2013 290<ref name=profbref />\n* Fewest interceptions in a regular season by starting quarterback \u2014 10  (2012) (16 starts)<ref name=profbref />\n* Most career fourth-quarter comeback wins \u2013 14<ref name=profbref />\n* Most career game-winning drives \u2013 21<ref name=profbref />\n* Most game-winning drives in a single season \u2013 4 (2010) (tied with [[Elvis Grbac]])<ref name=profbref />\n* Most passing yards in a single season \u2013 4,317 (2016)<ref name=profbref />\n* Most pass completions in a single season \u2013 436 (2016)<ref name=profbref />\n* Most pass attempts in a single season \u2013 672 (2016)<ref name=profbref />\n\n==Endorsements==\nFlacco signed a three-year contract with [[Reebok]] as a rookie in 2008.<ref name=\"Nike, Reebok Get Busy Signing NFL Draft rookies to Endorsement Deals\">{{cite web| url=http://www.blackvoices.com/blogs/2008/04/29/nike-reebok-get-busy-signing-nfl-draft-rookies-to-endorsement-d/ |title=Nike, Reebok Get Busy Signing NFL Draft rookies to Endorsement Deals |publisher=Blackvoices.com |date=April 29, 2008 |accessdate=April 29, 2008 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080501122131/http://www.blackvoices.com/blogs/2008/04/29/nike-reebok-get-busy-signing-nfl-draft-rookies-to-endorsement-d/ |archivedate=May 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> In 2009\u20132010, Flacco was a spokesperson for [[Pizza Hut]], which sold a product called \"Flacco's Favorites\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pizzahutpizza.com/flacco/ |title=Joe Flacco \u2013 Pizza Hut of Maryland |publisher=Pizzahutpizza.com |year=2009 |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091203202317/http://www.pizzahutpizza.com/flacco/ |archivedate=December 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Flacco has also endorsed [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]<ref name=\"Haribo\" /> and [[1st Mariner Bank]], as well as [[Haribo]] since January 2013.<ref name=\"Haribo\">{{cite web|last=Rovell |first=Darren |url= http://espn.go.com/blog/playbook/dollars/post/_/id/2828/flacco-signs-gummy-bear-endorsement-deal |title=Baltimore Ravens' Joe Flacco signs gummy bear endorsement deal |publisher=ESPN |date=January 29, 2013 |accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref> Also in 2013, Flacco signed an endorsement deal with [[McDonald's]] to promote their new menu item, the Mighty Wings.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2013/09/18/joe-flaccos-new-mcdonalds-ad-viewed-as-golden-opportunity/ |title=Joe Flacco's New McDonald's Ad Viewed As Golden Opportunity |publisher=CBS Baltimore |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> Flacco has also teamed up with [[opendorse]] to promote a [[Zynga]] mobile application called \"NFL Showdown: Football Manager\" as well as a line of women's apparel for [[Spirit Football Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/darrenheitner/2015/04/07/opendorse-raises-1-75-million-with-plans-to-make-athlete-endorsements-smarter/ |title=Opendorse Raises $1.75 Million With Plans To Make Athlete Endorsements Smarter |last=Heitner |first=Darren |date=April 7, 2015 |website=Forbes |access-date=August 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJoe Flacco married his wife Dana in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1514806-meet-dana-flacco-wife-of-super-bowl-mvp-joe-flacco |title=Meet Dana Flacco, Wife of Super Bowl MVP Joe Flacco |last=Carson |first=Dan |date=February 4, 2013 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> Together they have five children; their first child Stephen Flacco was born in June 2012,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/JoeFlacco/status/213290313639395332 |title=Joe Flacco on Twitter: \"On behalf of the Flacco family we're proud to announce the arrival of 8lb Stephen Flacco. Dana, baby & Joe are all doing well -Team Flacco\" |last=Flacco |first=Joe |date=June 14, 2012 |publisher=Twitter |access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> Daniel Flacco was born September 15, 2013, about an hour before the start of the Ravens' home opener.<ref>{{cite news|last=Boren|first=Cindy|title=Super Bowl 2013: Joe Flacco expects a payday and a baby|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2013/02/04/super-bowl-xlvii-joe-flacco-expects-a-payday-and-a-baby/|work=The Washington Post|date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> Francis Flacco was born in January 2015 and <ref>{{cite news|last=Meoli|first=Jon|title=Joe Flacco, wife Dana, welcome third child Tuesday night|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/baltimore-sports-blog/bal-joe-flacco-wife-dana-welcomed-third-child-tuesday-night-20150121-story.html|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=January 21, 2015|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> Thomas Flacco was born in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2018/04/13/joe-flacco-child/ |title=Joe Flacco And Wife Welcome Their 5th Child |date=April 13, 2018 |website=CBS - Baltimore |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> The Flaccos' only daughter, Evelyn Flacco, was born in September 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/The-Caw-Joe-Flaccos-Fourth-Baby-And-First-Daughter-Has-Arrived/6d9ef58e-1a2a-4cd7-aff1-fb47778cb1c3 |title=The Caw: Joe Flacco's Fourth Baby, And First Daughter, Has Arrived |last=Mink |first=Ryan |website=Baltimore Ravens |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117025113/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/The-Caw-Joe-Flaccos-Fourth-Baby-And-First-Daughter-Has-Arrived/6d9ef58e-1a2a-4cd7-aff1-fb47778cb1c3 |archive-date=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe is the oldest out of the five boys in his family. His brothers are named Mike, John, Brian, and Tom;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/marc_narducci/20110904_Marc_Narducci__Last_Flacco_stepping_in_at_Eastern.html%3Famphtml%3Dy |title=Last Flacco stepping in at Eastern |last=Narducci |first=Marc |website=Philadelphia Daily News |access-date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> He also has a sister named Stephanie. His brother Mike was selected in the 31st round of the [[2009 Major League Baseball draft]] by the [[Baltimore Orioles]], and was the starting first baseman for the [[Frederick Keys]], who won the 2011 [[Carolina League]] championship. He hit for a .250 average, with 5 HRs and 22 RBIs in 50 games with the Keys.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://orioles.scout.com/a.z?s=251&p=2&c=1088718&ssf=1&RequestedURL=http%3a%2f%2forioles.scout.com%2f2%2f1088718.html |title=Scout.com: Flacco Succeeding in Frederick |last=Vigliotti |first=Andrew |publisher=Scout.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929132547/http://orioles.scout.com/a.z?s=251&p=2&c=1088718&ssf=1&RequestedURL=http%3a%2f%2forioles.scout.com%2f2%2f1088718.html |archive-date=September 29, 2011 |access-date=July 23, 2011}}</ref> The Orioles traded him to the [[Boston Red Sox]] on March 15, 2013, and rather than accepting the assignment, Flacco decided to retire from baseball. He then enrolled at the [[University of New Haven]] to play football as a [[tight end]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Chisholm| first=Henry| url=http://nhregister.com/articles/2013/07/18/sports/doc51e84e7b1038f190905529.txt|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130719210510/http://nhregister.com/articles/2013/07/18/sports/doc51e84e7b1038f190905529.txt|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 19, 2013|title=NEW HAVEN FOOTBALL: Mike Flacco, Joe's brother, is newest Chargers tight end|work=New Haven Register|date=July 19, 2013|accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> and declared for the [[2014 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000310674/article/report-joe-flaccos-brother-declares-for-nfl-draft|title=Report: Joe Flacco's brother declares for NFL draft|publisher=[[National Football League]]|date=January 7, 2014|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>{{update inline|date=November 2015}} Another brother, John, was a walk-on receiver with the [[Stanford Cardinal football]] team and played against the [[Army Black Knights football]] team at the 2013 Stanford vs. Army football game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gostanford.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30600&ATCLID=208167708|title=Player Bio: John Flacco|publisher=Stanford University|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lombardi's Look Back: Army, Flacco Fever|date=September 16, 2013|publisher=Scout.com|last=Lombardi|first=David|accessdate=September 20, 2013|url=http://stanford.scout.com/2/1327151.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920000228/http://stanford.scout.com/2/1327151.html|archivedate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> Joe's youngest brother, Tom Flacco, enrolled in 2015 at [[Western Michigan University]], where he played quarterback for two seasons before transferring to [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]] in 2017 and then [[Towson Tigers football|Towson]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/broncos/index.ssf/2015/01/wmu_football_team_expected_to.html |title=Flacco is early enrollee at WMU |last=Drew |first=David |date=January 5, 2015 |publisher=MLive.com |access-date=January 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/06/07/joe-flaccos-brother-transferring-from-rutgers-too/ |title=Joe Flacco\u2019s brother transferring from Rutgers, too |last=Taylor |first=John |date=June 7, 2018 |work=CollegeFootballTalk |access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a survey by [[Fanatics (sports retailer)|Fanatics]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wearefanatics.com/most-attractive-nfl-teams/ |title=The Most Attractive NFL Teams |website=We Are Fanatics |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210123640/http://wearefanatics.com/most-attractive-nfl-teams/ |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> in January 2017, Flacco was elected as the most attractive player in the [[NFL]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/The-Caw-Joe-Flacco-Is-The-NFLs-Most-Attractive-Player/0690cae5-7419-40ca-aa51-49323f7b4ab0|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119014257/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/The-Caw-Joe-Flacco-Is-The-NFLs-Most-Attractive-Player/0690cae5-7419-40ca-aa51-49323f7b4ab0|archivedate=January 19, 2018|title=The Caw: Joe Flacco Is The NFL's Most Attractive Player|access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2017/02/09/survey-ravens-qb-joe-flacco-voted-most-attractive-in-nfl/ |title=Survey: Ravens QB Joe Flacco Voted Most Attractive In NFL |date=February 9, 2017 |website=CBS - Baltimore |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ravenswire.usatoday.com/2017/02/09/flacco-named-most-attractive-nfl-player/ |title=Flacco named most attractive NFL player |last=Stevens |first=Matthew |date=February 9, 2017 |website=Ravens Wire |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of National Football League career passing yards leaders]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Football stats |nfl=FLA009602 |espn=11252 |cbs= |yahoo=8795 |si=8795 |pfr=F/FlacJo00 |rotoworld=4677}}\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203181615/http://joeflacco5.com/ |date=December 3, 2011 |title=Official website}} \n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080418002136/http://www.udel.edu/sportsinfo/football/roster07-flacco.html |date=April 18, 2008 |title=Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens bio}} \n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127014812/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/roster/joe-flacco/3e20766f-6520-4ca1-9901-44389aaea8b8 |date=January 27, 2013 |title=Baltimore Ravens bio}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Joe Flacco\n| list =\n{{Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens quarterback navbox}}\n{{2008 NFL Draft}}\n{{RavensFirstPick}}\n{{Ravens2008DraftPicks}}\n{{Baltimore Ravens starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Denver Broncos starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Diet Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Year}}\n{{Super Bowl XLVII}}\n{{Super Bowl MVPs}}\n{{Super Bowl Champion quarterbacks}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flacco, Joe}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Audubon High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Ravens players]]\n[[Category:Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football players]]\n[[Category:People from Audubon, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Panthers football players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Camden County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl MVPs]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Joe Flacco\n| image = Joe Flacco 2019.JPG\n| image_size = 275\n| caption = Flacco with the Broncos in 2019\n| current_team = Free agent \n| number = \n| position = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1985|1|16|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Audubon, New Jersey]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lb = 245\n| high_school = [[Audubon High School|Audubon]]<br/>([[Audubon, New Jersey]])\n| college = [[Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football|Delaware]]\n| draftyear = 2008\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 18\n| pastteams = \n* [[Baltimore Ravens]] ({{NFL Year|2008}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Denver Broncos]]   ({{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status = Active\n| highlights = \n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLVII|XLVII]])\n* [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Super Bowl MVP]] ([[Super Bowl XLVII|XLVII]])\n* [[Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Year]] (2008)\n* [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] Player of the Year (2007)\n* First-team All-[[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]] (2007)\n* [[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]] Co-Offensive Player of the Year (2007)\n| statweek   = 17\n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = Passing attempts\n| statvalue1 = 5,932\n| statlabel2 = Passing completions\n| statvalue2 = 3,670\n| statlabel3 = Percentage\n| statvalue3 = 61.9\n| statlabel4 = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue4 = 218\u2013141\n| statlabel5 = Passing yards\n| statvalue5 = 40,067\n| statlabel6 = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue6 = 84.1\n| nfl-new = joeflacco/382\n|HOF= \n|CollegeHOF= \n}}\n\n'''Joseph Vincent Flacco''' (born January 16, 1985) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who is a free agent. He played [[college football]] at [[Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football|Delaware]] after transferring from [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]], and was drafted by the [[Baltimore Ravens]] in the first round of the [[2008 NFL Draft]].\n\nFlacco was Baltimore's starting quarterback from 2008 until midway through the [[2018 Baltimore Ravens season|2018 season]], and helped lead the Ravens to the playoffs six times; during his tenure in Baltimore the Ravens won the [[AFC North]] twice, appeared in three [[AFC Championship Game]]s, and defeated the [[San Francisco 49ers]] to win [[Super Bowl XLVII]] following the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens season|2012 season]]. Flacco was named Super Bowl XLVII's [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]], concluding a postseason run in which he tied [[Joe Montana]]'s single postseason record for touchdown passes (11) without an interception. That offseason, Flacco signed a six-year contract worth $120.6 million, a record high for a quarterback at the time.<ref name=\"extension\">{{cite news|last=McIntyre|first=Brian|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/ravens-joe-flacco-agree-terms-contract-extension-001509370--nfl.html|title=Ravens, Joe Flacco agree to terms on contract extension|work=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|date=March 1, 2013|accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref> Flacco was traded to the Broncos following the 2018 season following a hip injury that caused him to lose his starting position to [[Lamar Jackson]].\n\nDespite rather pedestrian regular season statistics and no [[Pro Bowl]] berths as of the [[2019 NFL season]], Flacco has proven himself as a better performer in the postseason,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/Why-Joe-Flacco-Is-So-Good-In-The-Playoffs/cf7661b0-932c-4396-879f-1cbcaa981640 |title=Why Joe Flacco is so good in the playoffs |last=Mink |first=Ryan |date=January 6, 2015 |website=BaltimoreRavens.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511073010/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/Why-Joe-Flacco-Is-So-Good-In-The-Playoffs/cf7661b0-932c-4396-879f-1cbcaa981640 |archive-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> having established a career playoff record of 10\u20135 and holding the record for most postseason road victories by a quarterback with seven. Flacco is also known for having one of the strongest arms in the NFL,<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosenthal|first=Gregg|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d82a4cb00/article/ron-jaworksi-joe-flacco-has-strongest-arm-in-nfl|title=Ron Jaworksi: Joe Flacco has strongest arm in NFL|publisher=National Football League|date=July 3, 2012|accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref> which allows him to use an \"aggressive, high-risk deep downfield passing game.\"<ref name=Byrne>{{cite news|last=Byrne|first=Kerry|title=Flacco, Eli have turned Super Bowl predictors upside down|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/nfl/news/20130204/joe-flacco-eli-manning-super-bowl-quarterbacks/?sct=uk_wr_a2|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=February 10, 2013|date=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nFlacco was born on January 16, 1985 in [[Audubon, New Jersey]]. The son of Karen (n\u00e9e Madden) and Steve Flacco,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gormley|first=Chuck|url=http://www.southjersey.com/articles/?articleid=20415|title=Ordinary Joe|work=South Jersey Magazine|volume=5|issue=12|publisher=SouthJersey.com|date=March 2009|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref> Joe is the oldest of five boys. The Flacco family is originally from [[Haddon Township, New Jersey]].\n\nFlacco played [[High school football|football]], [[baseball]], and [[basketball]] at [[Audubon High School]] and was the starting quarterback for the Green Wave.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/super-bowl/index.ssf/2013/01/super_bowl_xlvii_joe_flaccos_jersey_roots_keep_ravens_quarterback_humble_before_biggest_game_of_his.html |title=Super Bowl XLVII: Joe Flacco's Jersey roots keep him humble before biggest game of his life |work=The Star-Ledger |access-date=March 28, 2018 }}</ref> Regarded as a [[Star (classification)#American college football|three-star recruit]] by ''[[Rivals.com]]'', Flacco was listed as No. 39 among quarterback prospects in the class of 2003.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-189|title=Pro-style quarterbacks 2003|publisher=Rivals.com|date=February 5, 2003}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n===University of Pittsburgh===\nIn [[2003 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2003]], as part of the [[Pittsburgh Panthers football]] team, Flacco was [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] as a freshman for a team that went 8\u20135.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/pittsburgh/2003-schedule.html |title=2003 Pitt Panthers Schedule and Results |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2004 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|2004]], Flacco was the backup quarterback behind starter [[Tyler Palko]], who lead the team to an 8\u20134 record.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/pittsburgh/2004.html |title=2004 Pitt Panthers Stats |access-date=March 28, 2018 }}</ref> He saw action in three games against [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio University]], [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|University of Nebraska]], and the [[South Florida Bulls football|University of South Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-12-04-south-florida.html |title=Pitt at South Florida Box Score, December 4, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com &nbsp;|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Flacco threw only four passes and finished the season with one completion for 11 yards<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/joe-flacco-1/gamelog/2004/ |title=Joe Flacco 2004 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> and a 25-yard [[Punt (gridiron football)|punt]].\n\n===University of Delaware===\n[[File:Joe Flacco Delaware.jpg|thumb|upright|Flacco playing for Delaware in the 2007 FCS championship game]]\nFlacco transferred to the [[University of Delaware]] in 2005, but was not eligible to play that season.<ref>[https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bs-sp-ravens-flacco-1029-20161028-story.html]</ref> He saw his first full-time action during the [[2006 Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football team|2006 season]], throwing for 2,783 yards, 18 touchdowns and 10 interceptions.<ref name=\"totalfootballstats1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfootballstats.com/PlayerQB.asp?id=1203436|title=Joe Flacco College & Pro Football Statistics |publisher=Totalfootballstats.com|accessdate=January 13, 2013}}</ref> Delaware's [[Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football|Fightin' Blue Hens]] ultimately struggled to a 5\u20136 record and failed to qualify for the FCS playoffs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bluehens.com/SportSelect.dbml?&SPSID=670228&SPID=110401&DB_OEM_ID_COUNT_=2&DB_OEM_ID_1_=29100&DB_OEM_ID=29100&DB_OEM_ID_0_=29100&Q_SEASON=2006 |title=Football \u2013 Schedule \u2013 Delaware |website=Delaware Blue Hens Athletics |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2007 Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football team|2007 season]], Flacco led his team to an 8\u20133 regular season record while compiling 4,263 yards, 23 touchdowns and 5 interceptions.<ref name=\"totalfootballstats1\"/> Arguably his best game came against [[2007 Navy Midshipmen football team|Navy]] where he threw for 434 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=273002426 |title=Delaware Fightin Blue Hens vs. Navy Midshipmen \u2013 Box Score \u2013 October 27, 2007 |publisher=ESPN |date=October 27, 2007 |accessdate=January 13, 2013}}</ref> Flacco showed another solid performance in the first-ever meeting against the [[Delaware State Hornets football|Delaware State Hornets]] in the first round of the playoffs. Behind [[Omar Cuff]]'s record-setting day, Flacco threw efficiently for 189 yards and a touchdown, leading the Blue Hens to an easy 44\u20137 victory.<ref name=\"UDstats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bluehens.com/sportsinfo/football/stats07.html |title=2007 University of Delaware Football FINAL Statistics |publisher=University of Delaware |accessdate=January 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202161003/http://www.bluehens.com/sportsinfo/football/stats07.html |archivedate=February 2, 2012  }}</ref> Flacco continued Delaware's playoff run by upsetting the [[2007 Northern Iowa Panthers football team|Northern Iowa Panthers]] 39\u201327 in the [[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] quarterfinals and upsetting the [[Southern Illinois Salukis football|Southern Illinois Salukis]] 20\u201317 the next weekend in the semifinals. Flacco threw two touchdowns to win against both the Panthers and Salukis, but went on to lose in the championship game to the [[2007 Appalachian State Mountaineers football team|Appalachian State Mountaineers]] 49\u201321.<ref name=\"UDstats\"/>\n\nFlacco set 20 school records during his career at Delaware.<ref name=\"UD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluehens.com/sportsinfo/football/fb08-flaccodraft.html |title=Delaware Quarterback Joe Flacco Selected 18th Overall by Baltimore in First Round of National Football League Draft |date=April 26, 2008 |publisher=University of Delaware |accessdate=March 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105055449/http://www.bluehens.com/sportsinfo/football/fb08-flaccodraft.html |archivedate=January 5, 2009 }}</ref> In early September 2009, a 20- by 30-foot poster of Flacco was added to the facade of [[Delaware Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Tresolini |first=Kevin |url=http://blogs.delawareonline.com/collegesports/2009/09/15/delaware-stadium-gets-a-new-look-on-the-outside/ |title=Delaware Stadium gets a new look on the outside |publisher=Delawareonline.com |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}{{subscription needed}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 6\u215c\n|       weight = 236\n|         dash = 4.84\n|    ten split = 1.62\n| twenty split = 2.79\n|      shuttle = 4.27\n|   cone drill = 6.82\n|     vertical = 28\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 2\n|        bench =\n|    wonderlic = 27\n|     arm span =\n|    hand span =\n|         note = All values from the [[NFL Combine]]<ref>[http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=9300&draftyear=2008&genpos=QB Joe Flacco 2008 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile] nfldraftscout.com</ref>\n}}\n\nAt Delaware, Flacco was pessimistic about his chances to play in the NFL, and after his junior year asked his coach for permission to play baseball. The coach predicted that he would be selected in the [[NFL Draft]], surprising Flacco.<ref name=\"battista20130205\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/05/sports/football/ravens-to-pay-for-joe-flaccos-exquisite-timing.html?pagewanted=all|title=A Top-Tier Quarterback Set to Be Paid Like One|work=The New York Times|date=February 5, 2013|accessdate=February 4, 2013|author=Battista, Judy|page=B9}}</ref> With a solid showing at the [[2008 Senior Bowl|Senior Bowl]] and [[NFL Combine]], Flacco solidified himself as a top five quarterback in the [[2008 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/insider/news/story?id=3212538|title=Flacco continues to improve; North return men are impressive|publisher=ESPN Insider|date=January 24, 2008|accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref>  Flacco won the long distance throw competition in ESPN's State Farm College Football All-Star Challenge with a 74-yard throw, beating out [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]], [[Colt Brennan]], [[Chad Henne]], and [[John David Booty]], later winning the [[Taco Bell]] Quarterback Scramble with a time of 15.72 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jlsports.net/news_statefarm.html|title=State Farm College Football All-Star Challenge|publisher=jlsports.net|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMembers of the [[Baltimore Ravens]]' front office, having attended Flacco's workout at the Senior Bowl, were impressed by his ability to throw in rainy and windy conditions. Flacco again impressed the Ravens' personnel in the poor weather conditions of his workout at Delaware, despite their low expectations given Delaware's small-school pedigree\u2014Flacco performed the workout on an uncut, unlined field with his own footballs. Ravens assistant general manager [[Eric DeCosta]] later stated the workouts left him confident Flacco could succeed in the late-season conditions in Pittsburgh and Cleveland.<ref name=EJManuel>{{cite news|last=Judge|first=Clarke|title=EJ Manuel a bad-weather QB? It sealed the deal for the Buffalo Bills|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/blog/clark-judge/22172567/manuel-a-badweather-qb-it-sealed-the-deal-for-bills|work=CBSSports.com|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Baltimore Ravens===\nFlacco was drafted by the Ravens with the 18th overall pick in the [[2008 NFL Draft]] after the team traded out of the eight overall selection to the 26th, then up again.<ref name=EJManuel/>  The selection made Flacco the highest drafted player ever from the [[University of Delaware]].<ref name=\"UD\"/> He was also the first Division I-FCS (formerly I-AA) quarterback selected in the first round of the draft since [[Steve McNair]] went third overall to the [[Houston Oilers]] in the [[1995 NFL Draft]].  Draft commentators initially criticized the pick as a \"reach\", feeling Flacco would likely have still been available in the middle of the second round.  DeCosta, however, stated waiting was too much of a gamble and that choosing Flacco in the first round was \"an easy decision to make.\"<ref name=EJManuel/>\n\nOn July 16, 2008, he signed a five-year contract with a maximum value of around $30 million, and $8.75 million guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3492721 |title=Agent: Flacco agrees to five-year deal with Ravens |last=Walker |first=James |date=July 17, 2008 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2008 season====\n[[File:7 Boller 5 Flacco.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Flacco (right) and Boller during 2008 training camp]]\nDue to a season-ending injury to incumbent starter [[Kyle Boller]] and an illness to former [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Troy Smith]], Flacco became the starting quarterback in the 2008 season opener against the [[2008 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]]. He completed 15 of 29 passes for 129 yards, his longest pass being a 15-yard play to [[Derrick Mason]]. He threw no touchdowns and no interceptions in his debut, but he had a 38-yard rushing touchdown,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hensley|first=Jamison|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/football/bal-sp.ravens08sep08002019,0,2365173.story|title=Flacco off and running in debut|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> which was the longest rushing touchdown by a quarterback in Ravens' franchise history. Flacco's touchdown put the Ravens up by  17\u20133; the team eventually won the game 17\u201310.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809070rav.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 September 7th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Ravens vs Steelers 2008 MNF.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Flacco (crouching) lines up against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in 2008.]]\n\nIn his first season, Flacco was named AFC Offensive Player of the Week in Week 9, NFL Rookie of the week, the NFLPA Rookie of the week, and NFL Rookie of the Month for November. Flacco finished his rookie season 257/428 for 2,971 yards with a total of 16 touchdowns (14 passing, 2 rushing), and 14 turnovers (12 interceptions and 2 lost fumbles).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/week_9.htm |title=2008 NFL Week 9 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlacJo00/gamelog/2008/ |title=Joe Flacco 2008 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the wild card round of the [[2008\u201309 NFL playoffs]], Flacco became only the third rookie quarterback in NFL history to win his first post-season start, and the first to do it on the road, when his Ravens defeated the [[2008 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]], 27\u20139. Flacco completed 9-of-23 attempted passes, accumulating 135 yards without throwing a touchdown or interception. He also scored the victory-sealing rushing touchdown on a quarterback draw in the 4th quarter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200901040mia.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at Miami Dolphins \u2013 January 4th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> [[Shaun King (American football)|Shaun King]], [[Ben Roethlisberger]], [[Russell Wilson]], and [[Mark Sanchez]] are the only other rookie quarterbacks to ever win their debut playoff game.\n\nHe then won his second game versus the [[2008 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]]. Flacco led the Ravens to a 13\u201310 win in the divisional playoff round. Flacco made tight-window throws to [[Todd Heap]] and [[Mark J. Clayton|Mark Clayton]] on the go ahead scoring drive in the 4th quarter to set up a game-winning field goal from [[Matt Stover]]. On the day, Flacco was 11-of-22 for 148 yards and a touchdown, without turning the ball over for the second straight game. He became the first rookie quarterback to win two playoff games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hensley|first=Jamison|title=Joe Cool \u2013 Eerie Calm Drives Rookie From 3rd String to First Postseason|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2009-01-04/news/0901040008_1_joe-flacco-joe-cool-ravens|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=January 4, 2009|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2008\u201309 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: Pittsburgh Steelers 23, Baltimore Ravens 14|2009 AFC Championship Game]] versus the [[2008 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]], the Ravens lost 23\u201314, with Flacco throwing for 141 yards, being sacked a three times and throwing three picks, one being the game clincher to [[Troy Polamalu]], who returned the pass for a touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bishop|first=Greg|title=Steelers\u2019 Defense Rattles Normally Steady Flacco|work=The New York Times|date=January 19, 2008|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/19/sports/football/19bishop.html?ref=football|accessdate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFlacco was named the [[Diet Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Year]] in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/Joe-Flacco-Named-2008-Diet-Pepsi-Rookie-of-the-Year/C710CAE3-0328-40B1-95D9-A4FDB5E81133 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118235047/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/article-1/Joe-Flacco-Named-2008-Diet-Pepsi-Rookie-of-the-Year/C710CAE3-0328-40B1-95D9-A4FDB5E81133 |archivedate=January 18, 2018 |title=Joe Flacco Named 2008 Diet Pepsi Rookie of the Year |last=Duffy |first=Mike |work=Baltimore Ravens |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2009 season====\n[[File:Joe Flacco 2.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Flacco at Ravens Training Camp in 2008]]\nIn the season opening game in Baltimore against the [[2009 Kansas City Chiefs|Kansas City Chiefs]], Joe Flacco led the Ravens to their first win of the season. He threw for 307 yards and three touchdowns, both career highs, along with 18 yards rushing. He also threw one interception and had a quarterback rating of 95.8.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909130rav.htm |title=Kansas City Chiefs at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 September 13th, 2009 |access-date=December 30, 2017 }}</ref> During this game, the Ravens broke the franchise record for most offensive yards in a game with a total of 501.\n\nIn Week 15 against the [[2009 Chicago Bears|Chicago Bears]], Flacco broke his personal record for most touchdowns thrown in a game with four, while throwing for 234 passing yards and completing 72 percent of his passes, earning him a career-high [[passer rating]] of 135.6. The Ravens would go on to win the game 31\u20137.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200912200rav.htm |title=Chicago Bears at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 December 20th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> With 3,613 yards and 21 touchdowns, Flacco became the first Ravens quarterback since [[Vinny Testaverde]] to throw for more than 3,000 yards and more than 20 touchdowns in a single season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rav/single-season-passing.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens Single-Season Passing Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He also tied his interception number from his rookie season of 12.\n\nAn injury limited Flacco's performance Wild Card Weekend against the [[2009 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]]. The Ravens routed the Patriots 33\u201314 despite Flacco throwing 4-of-10 for just 34 yards with one interception.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201001100nwe.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 10th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Joe Flacco training camp.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Flacco drops back to pass during practice.]]\n\n====2010 season====\nIn the season opener, Flacco and the Ravens opened [[New Meadowlands Stadium]] against the [[2010 New York Jets|New York Jets]]. Flacco threw for 248 yards while completing 52.6% of his passes, throwing one interception and losing a fumble. In a defensive contest, the Ravens came away with the 10\u20139 win over their former defensive coordinator [[Rex Ryan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009130nyj.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at New York Jets \u2013 September 13th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 2 at the [[2010 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]], Flacco had arguably his worst NFL start of his young career, throwing for 154 yards while completing just 43.6% of his passes and throwing a career-high four interceptions, while throwing one touchdown and accumulating a passer rating of 23.8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009190cin.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Cincinnati Bengals \u2013 September 19th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Coming off of the worst start of his career, {{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} Flacco and the Ravens had their home opener against the [[2010 Cleveland Browns|Cleveland Browns]]. Flacco bounced back from his Week 2 loss to the Bengals and had his best game of the young season, throwing for 262-yards and completing 71% of his passes. He then hooked up with prized offseason acquisition wide receiver [[Anquan Boldin]] for three touchdowns, while throwing no interceptions and accumulating a passer rating of 128.7. The Ravens won the contest 24\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009260rav.htm |title=Cleveland Browns at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 September 26th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 26, 2010, with a win against the Cleveland Browns, Flacco became one of only four NFL quarterbacks to lead his team to the playoffs in all three of his first three seasons. During this game, Flacco reached 10,000 career passing yards. Ending the season, Flacco set season highs in passing yards (3,622), passing touchdowns (25), passer rating (93.6), and a season low in interceptions (10), yet set a career-high with four lost fumbles.\n\nIn defeating the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs|Kansas City Chiefs]] (30\u20137) in the wildcard round of the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs]], Flacco completed 25 of 34 passes for 265 yards and two touchdowns, with no interceptions, for a post-season-high passer rating of 115.4.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101090kan.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 9th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> With the win, Flacco became the first quarterback in NFL history to start and win a playoff game in each of his first three seasons, and tied [[Len Dawson]], [[Roger Staubach]], [[Jake Delhomme]], and [[Mark Sanchez]] for most career post-season road wins by a quarterback.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/don_banks/01/13/ravens-steelers/|title=Inside the NFL|last=Banks |first=Don|work=Sports Illustrated|date=January 13, 2011|accessdate=January 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the divisional round, Flacco and the Ravens would once again head to Pittsburgh to play their arch-rival [[2010 Pittsburgh Steelers|Steelers]]. The difference this time would be the season was on the line. The Ravens got out to an early 21\u20137 lead after a 12-yard rush by running back [[Ray Rice]], a fumble recovery run back for a touchdown by defensive end [[Cory Redding]], and a four-yard touchdown pass from Flacco to tight end [[Todd Heap]]. But in the third quarter, which the Ravens had been dominant in all of the regular season, Baltimore fell apart. The Ravens turned the ball over three times in their own territory with an uncharacteristic fumble by Rice, an interception by Flacco, and a fumbled snap by Center [[Matt Birk]] (Flacco was credited with the lost fumble), and with those the Steelers took a 31\u201324 lead. But even after all of the Ravens miscues and errors, the Ravens still had a shot to win it at the end when Flacco threw a dart to Houshmandzadeh, but it was dropped. Flacco finished the game 16-of-30 for 125 yards, one touchdown, and one interception.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101150pit.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 15th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He was ranked 90th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2011]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/videos/videos/Top-100--Joe-Flacco/d10d1275-fc05-43aa-aaba-44dc53f012ec |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328102731/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/videos/videos/Top-100--Joe-Flacco/d10d1275-fc05-43aa-aaba-44dc53f012ec |archivedate=March 28, 2018 |title=Top 100:  Joe Flacco |website=Baltimore Ravens |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\nFlacco had his best game of the season in Week 3 against the [[2011 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]]. He went 27-of-48 with a season-high 389 yards through the air and three touchdowns, all in the first quarter and to rookie wideout Torrey Smith (who actually finished the game with a five catch, 152-yard breakout performance). Flacco had a 103.6 rating, as well as 27 yards rushing and a lost fumble. The Ravens scored a season-high 37 points in the 30-point blowout victory, and also gained a franchise record 553 offensive yards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109110rav.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 September 11th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFlacco had three more 300-yard games during the regular season: against the [[2011 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]], [[2011 Arizona Cardinals|Arizona Cardinals]] and Steelers in a ''Sunday Night Football'' matchup. He won all three of these games, sweeping Pittsburgh for the first time in his career, but also lost fumbles in each one.\nDespite losing to the [[2011 San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] in Week 15, the Ravens clinched the playoffs for the fourth straight year that week. The Ravens clinched their division, along with the number 2 seed in the AFC, in a Week 17 win over the rival [[2011 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]]. Flacco threw for 130 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201010cin.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Cincinnati Bengals \u2013 January 1st, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rav/2011.htm |title=2011 Baltimore Ravens Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFlacco finished the season starting all 16 games. He had 312 completions on 542 attempts (57.6%). He threw for 3,610 yards, 20 touchdowns, 12 interceptions, and had one rushing score. He averaged 225.6 yards per game, was sacked 31 times over the course of the season and set a new career high with six lost fumbles. He finished the year with an 80.9 QB rating.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlacJo00/gamelog/2011/ |title=Joe Flacco 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/joeflacco/382/profile|title=Joe Flacco|publisher=National Football League|accessdate=August 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlacco continued his playoff dominance that year. In the [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs|Divisional playoff game]] against the Houston Texans, he threw for 176 yards and two touchdowns, with no turnovers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201150rav.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Houston Texans at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 January 15th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> In the AFC Championship Game, Flacco completed 22 out of his 36 attempts while throwing for two touchdowns and one interception along with 306 yards passing. These stats were enough to outplay [[2011 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]] quarterback [[Tom Brady]], who threw for 67 fewer yards, 2 fewer touchdowns, and 1 more interception than Flacco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/boxscore?gameId=320122017|title=Baltimore Ravens vs. New England Patriots \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 22, 2012 |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=August 15, 2015}}</ref> Despite Flacco's performance, the Patriots won to advance to the Super Bowl.\n\n====2012 season: Super Bowl MVP====\nOn the NFL Network's [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2012|Top 100 Players of 2012 list]], Flacco was ranked 74th by his fellow players.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/baltimore-ravens/09000d5d828fa08e/Top-100-Players-of-2012-Joe-Flacco |title='Top 100 Players of 2012': Joe Flacco |publisher=National Football League  |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref> Despite Flacco's success\u2014the Ravens were in the playoffs each of his first four seasons{{r|battista20130205}}\u2014few saw him as among the NFL's best quarterbacks. Before January 2015, he had never been selected for the [[Pro Bowl]].<ref name=\"klemko20130204\">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/ravens/2013/02/04/super-bowl-xlvii-baltimore-ravens-mvp-quarterback-joe-flacco-wife-dana-pregnant/1889933/ | title=Partying with Super Bowl MVP Joe Flacco means parents, pop | work=USA Today | date=February 4, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2013 | author=Klemko, Robert}}</ref> In April 2012 Flacco was, as ''The New York Times'' later stated, \"almost universally mocked\" when he stated that he was the best quarterback in the NFL, superior to Brady, [[Peyton Manning]], or [[Aaron Rodgers]]. \"I don\u2019t think I\u2019d be very successful at my job if I didn\u2019t feel that way\", Flacco said.<ref name=\"borden20130204\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/04/sports/football/super-bowl-joe-flaccos-precision-typical-of-elite-quarterbacks.html | title=Flacco's Precision Typical of Elite Quarterbacks | work=The New York Times | date=February 4, 2013 | accessdate=February 4, 2013 | author=Borden, Sam | pages=D1}}</ref> In July, he turned down the Raven's offer of a new contract, reportedly for $16 million a year, telling his agent that he believed he could improve and earn more.{{r|battista20130205}}\n\n[[File:Joe Flacco under center vs Pittsburgh Steelers 12-2-12.jpg|right|thumb|Flacco under center against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] on December 2, 2012]]\nIn the opening week, Flacco passed for 299 yards and two touchdowns in a 44\u201313 victory over the [[2012 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]] to earn his second AFC Offensive Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209100rav.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 September 10th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/week_1.htm |title=2012 NFL Week 1 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref> By Week 11, the Ravens had amassed a 9\u20132 record. Flacco played poorly however once again in a Week 12 rematch with the Steelers, completing only 16 of 34 passes for 188 yards with one touchdown and an interception. The game saw the Ravens squander a ten-point lead and lose 20\u201323, despite their division rival starting backup [[Charlie Batch]] at quarterback.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212020rav.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 December 2nd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The following week against the [[2012 Washington Redskins|Washington Redskins]], Flacco went 16-of-21 with three touchdowns but again amassed less than 200 passing yards in the season's first back-to-back losses.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212090was.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Washington Redskins \u2013 December 9th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> With the offense remaining inconsistent and the team missing opportunities to win their division with each loss, offensive coordinator [[Cam Cameron]] was unexpectedly fired and replaced by quarterbacks coach \u2013 and former Indianapolis Colts head coach \u2013 [[Jim Caldwell (American football)|Jim Caldwell]]. The change at coordinator was followed by a lopsided loss to the Denver Broncos, leading to widespread criticism of Flacco in the media.<ref name=Schmuck>{{cite web|last=Schmuck|first=Peter|title=Ravens lost four of last five regular season games, but never lost faith|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bs-sp-schmuck-ravens-column-0210-20130207,0,3460701.column|work=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:JoeFlacco09232012.JPG|thumb|Flacco warms up before a home game versus the New England Patriots in 2012.]]\nFlacco and the Ravens responded with a decisive, 33\u201314 win over the defending Super Bowl-champion [[2012 New York Giants|New York Giants]] in which Flacco threw for 309 yards and two touchdowns, with another rushing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212230rav.htm |title=New York Giants at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 December 23rd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Despite the victory over New York, much of the local and national media wrote the team off as Super Bowl contenders,<ref>{{cite web|last=Judge|first=Clark|title=Another win seems improbable for free-falling Ravens|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/story/21411467/another-win-seems-improbable-for-freefalling-ravens|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> with ESPN writing that the team had \"backed into the playoffs with a disastrous December.\"<ref name=AFCNB>{{cite web|last=Hensley|first=Jamison|title=Ravens proving to be team of destiny|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcnorth/post/_/id/63442/baltimore-ravens-proving-to-be-team-of-destiny|work=AFC North Blog|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2013, in the [[2012\u201313 NFL Playoffs|Wild Card Playoffs]] round against the [[2013 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]], Flacco finished the game 12 of 23 for 282 yards, two touchdowns, and a career postseason high 125.6 passer rating.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301060rav.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 January 6th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The 24\u20139 win at home set up a [[Mile High Miracle|Divisional round rematch with the Broncos]], who entered the game as nine-point favorites after their regular season win over the Ravens, which included a 98-yard interception touchdown return by Broncos' cornerback [[Chris Harris (cornerback)|Chris Harris]] that marked the lowest point of Flacco's season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hensley|first=Jamison|title=Turning point of Joe Flacco's season|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcnorth/post/_/id/64029/turning-point-of-joe-flaccos-season|work=AFC North Blog|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>  Continuing his postseason success, Flacco played one of the best games in his career, throwing for 331 yards and 3 touchdowns. In the fourth quarter, the Ravens were down 35\u201328 and had one last chance to tie the game. After an incomplete pass and a 7-yard scramble, on 3rd down and 3, Flacco heaved a 70-yard touchdown pass to [[Jacoby Jones]], sending the game into overtime. The pass has been called the \"[[Mile High Miracle]]\", and \"one of the greatest plays in NFL history\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Shwab|first=Frank|title=Joe Flacco validates himself with a Super Bowl MVP award|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/joe-flacco-validates-himself-super-bowl-mvp-award-035953835--nfl.html|work=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref> and drew comparisons to [[Roger Staubach]]'s \"[[Hail Mary pass|Hail Mary]]\", [[Terry Bradshaw]]'s \"[[Immaculate Reception]]\", and [[Joe Montana]]'s \"[[The Catch (American football)|The Catch]]\".<ref name=Pells>{{cite news|last=Pells|first=Eddie|title=Ravens Beat Broncos 38\u201335 In Double OT: Flacco, Jones, Tucker Lead Baltimore To AFC Title Game|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/12/ravens-broncos-38-35-double-overtime_n_2464949.html|work=HuffPost|accessdate=February 5, 2013|date=January 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Greenberg|first=Chris|title=Jacoby Jones Touchdown: Joe Flacco Throws 70-Yard TD, Sending Ravens To Overtime (VIDEO)|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/12/jacoby-jones-touchdown-joe-flacco_n_2465119.html|work=HuffPost|accessdate=February 5, 2013|date=January 12, 2013}}</ref>  The Ravens would go on to win the game in double overtime 38\u201335 after an interception by [[Corey Graham]] from Peyton Manning and a 47-yard field goal from [[Justin Tucker]], sending the Ravens to face the New England Patriots in the AFC Championship for a second straight year.<ref name=Pells/>\n\nOn January 20, 2013, Flacco and the Ravens avenged the previous year's AFC Championship Game loss to the [[2012 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] with a 28\u201313 win, securing their spot in the 2013 Super Bowl.  Flacco threw for 240 yards and three touchdowns, notching his third straight game with a passer rating over 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301200nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 20th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>  With this win, Flacco became the second NFL quarterback to defeat both [[Peyton Manning]] (with the Broncos) and [[Tom Brady]] in the same postseason since both became starting quarterbacks in 2001 (the first to do so was [[Mark Sanchez]] in 2010).\n\n[[File:Joe Flacco passes to Ray Rice in Super Bowl XLVII.jpg|thumb|left|Flacco attempts a pass to [[Ray Rice]] in [[Super Bowl XLVII]], which Baltimore won 34\u201331 over the [[2012 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]].]]\n\nIn a 34\u201331 win over the favored San Francisco 49ers in [[Super Bowl XLVII]], played on February 3, 2013, Flacco completed 22 of 33 passes for 287 yards and another three touchdowns, tying him for first place on the list of [[Most consecutive games with a touchdown pass (NFL)#All-time consecutive playoff games with at least three touchdown passes|most consecutive playoff games with at least three touchdown passes]] (3 games).  With a record fourth playoff game with a 100+ passer rating in a single postseason,<ref name=Byrne/> Flacco was named the game's [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]].{{r|borden20130204}} For winning the award, he was given a then-brand-new red [[Chevrolet Corvette]].\n\nFlacco finished the postseason having completed 73-of-126 (57.9 percent) passes for 1,140 yards with 11 touchdowns and zero interceptions, tying Montana and [[Kurt Warner]] for the most touchdowns in a single postseason<ref name=Klemko>{{cite news|last=Klemko|first=Robert|title=Ravens' Flacco fulfills promise with Super Bowl victory|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/ravens/2013/02/03/super-bowl-47-joe-flacco-baltimore-ravens/1889399/|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 5, 2013|date=February 3, 2013}}</ref> and additionally tying Montana for the most touchdowns without an interception in a single postseason.<ref name=Barnwell>{{cite web|last=Barnwell|first=Bill|title=Super Bowl Redux|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8912868/bill-barnwell-puts-ravens-win-perspective|publisher=[[Grantland.com]]|accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref>  Flacco's 117.2 passer rating tied him for third place all-time with [[Steve Young]] in a Super Bowl-winning postseason.<ref name=Barnwell/>\n\nThese accomplishments gave Flacco what ''The New York Times'' stated \"might be the best start to a player's [[Free agent|free agency]] in the history of professional sports\", as his contract expired after the season.{{r|borden20130204}} He was ranked 19th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2013]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/baltimore-ravens/0ap2000000212721/Robert-Mathis-Jameel-McClain-Ben-Watson-Ike-Taylor-Haloti-Ngata-Champ-Bailey |title='Top 100 Players of 2013':  Joe Flacco |publisher=National Football League  |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\nOn March 4, 2013, Flacco became the highest-paid quarterback in NFL history when he signed a six-year contract worth $120.6 million.<ref name=\"extension\"/> However, within months, he was surpassed by the [[Green Bay Packers|Packers]]' [[Aaron Rodgers]]<ref name=\"theblaze\">{{cite web|title=FIND OUT WHICH QB JUST BECAME THE HIGHEST PAID PLAYER IN NFL HISTORY|url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/04/26/find-out-which-qb-just-became-the-highest-paid-player-in-nfl-history/|publisher=[[TheBlaze]]|accessdate=April 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201449/http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/04/26/find-out-which-qb-just-became-the-highest-paid-player-in-nfl-history/|archive-date=October 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the [[Atlanta Falcons|Falcons]]' [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hensley|first=Jamison|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcnorth/post/_/id/72490/flacco-is-now-nfls-third-highest-paid-qb|title=Flacco is now NFL's third-highest paid QB|work=AFC North Blog|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFlacco's 2013 season was statistically the worst of his career. For the first time as an NFL quarterback, Flacco threw more interceptions than he threw touchdowns. His 22 interceptions in the season were 10 more than he had thrown in any other season. His 19 touchdowns were also his lowest since his rookie year. His passer rating was a career low 73.1, approximately 7 points lower than Flacco's previous worst season passer rating. He was also sacked more times (48) than he was in any other season in his career. Despite all this, he also set a high in passing yards, with 3,912.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/joeflacco/382/careerstats|title=Joe Flacco: Career Stats at NFL.com|publisher=National Football League|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> The Ravens finished 8\u20138 for the season and Flacco missed the playoffs for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rav/2013.htm |title=2013 Baltimore Ravens Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He was ranked 58th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/videos/videos/NFLN-Top-100-Players-of-2014-Joe-Flacco/64677e80-b694-4adb-9e00-571e16f15774 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328102710/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/videos/videos/NFLN-Top-100-Players-of-2014-Joe-Flacco/64677e80-b694-4adb-9e00-571e16f15774 |archivedate=March 28, 2018 |title=NFLN: 'Top 100 Players of 2014': Joe Flacco |website=Baltimore Ravens |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\n[[File:Joe Flacco 2014.jpg|right|thumb|Joe Flacco versus the Carolina Panthers in 2014]]\nIn their 2014 season home opener, the Ravens played against the division rival [[2014 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]]. The game saw the Ravens trailing practically the entire time; however, their one lead of the game came off of an 80-yard touchdown pass from Flacco to wide receiver [[Steve Smith Sr.]]. As of the 2016 season, it was the longest throw of Flacco's career. However, the Ravens would go on to lose the game 23\u201316, after Bengals' quarterback [[Andy Dalton]] connected with receiver [[A. J. Green]] for an even more stupendous 77-yard touchdown that would ultimately be the game winner.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070rav.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 September 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> It would be the first time since 2005 that the Ravens lost their home opener. Flacco finished the game completing 35 of 62 passes and throwing for a season-high 345 passing yards along with a touchdown and an interception, with a passer rating of 71.0.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/joeflacco/382/gamelogs|title=Joe Flacco: Game Logs at NFL.com|publisher=National Football League|accessdate=August 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFlacco had his best game of the season in Week 6, and one of the best games of his career. He completed 21 of 28 passes for 306 yards and a career-high five touchdown passes to four different receivers (Smith Sr., Torrey Smith, [[Kamar Aiken]] and [[Michael Campanaro]]) with no interceptions. He once again wasn't sacked and had a season-high passer rating of 149.7. Flacco became the fastest quarterback to throw five touchdown passes, as it only took him 16 minutes and 3 seconds. The Ravens blew out the [[2014 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] 48\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410120tam.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 October 12th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He earned AFC Offensive Player of the Week honors for the third time in his career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/week_6.htm |title=2014 NFL Week 6 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 16, the Ravens took on the [[2014 Houston Texans|Houston Texans]] with a chance to clinch the playoffs. Flacco played his worst game of the season, and arguably the worst of his career. He ended the first half with only 27 passing yards and two interceptions, as the Ravens trailed 16\u20130 going into halftime. The Ravens would rally in the second half, as Flacco threw two touchdown passes to Torrey Smith, but the Ravens never held a lead in the entire game and ended up losing 25\u201313. Flacco finished completing 21 of 50 passes for 195 yards, two touchdowns and three interceptions with a season-low passer rating of 41.7. He was also sacked twice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412210htx.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Houston Texans \u2013 December 21st, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 17, the Ravens took on the [[2014 Cleveland Browns|Cleveland Browns]] in Baltimore. They had the chance to clinch the final playoff seed, but they needed a win and for the Kansas City Chiefs to beat or tie the San Diego Chargers. Trailing 10\u20136 in the fourth quarter, Flacco stepped up big time. He heaved a deep pass to Torrey Smith, who caught the ball at the Browns' 16 yard line. On the next play of the game, Flacco connected with Smith again, this time for a touchdown, which put the Ravens up 13\u201310 for good with 7:33 left in the game. With 3:44 left in the game, Flacco threw another touchdown pass to Kamar Aiken, sealing a 20\u201310 win. Kansas City would beat San Diego 19\u20137, giving Baltimore the final AFC playoff spot. Flacco finished the game with 22 of 36 completed passes, 312 passing yards, 2 touchdowns and no interceptions with a passer rating of 107.6. Flacco was also sacked one time, which caused one of his two fumbles in the game (he did not lose either).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412280rav.htm |title=Cleveland Browns at Baltimore Ravens \u2013 December 28th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n2014 saw Flacco have the best regular season of his career. He set highs in passing yards (3,986), passing touchdowns (27), times sacked (19), fumbles (5) and fumbles lost (0). He also attempted and completed the second most single-season passes in his career (344 completions out of 554 attempts) and tied his mark for second fewest interceptions thrown in a regular season (12). From Weeks 2 through 4, Flacco was not sacked at all. In 5 of Flacco's last 6 games of the season, his passer rating was 99 or higher, with the one exception being the 25\u201313 loss to Houston. He led Baltimore to a 10\u20136 record.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlacJo00/gamelog/2014/ |title=Joe Flacco 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Wild Card round of the playoffs, the Ravens played the AFC North-winning [[2014 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]] at [[Heinz Field]]. Flacco completed 18 of 29 passes for 259 yards, two touchdowns and no interceptions with a passer rating of 114.0, as the Ravens beat the Steelers 30\u201317. He was sacked once, after getting tripped up by his offensive lineman on the Ravens' first offensive play of the game. This became the first time that the Ravens beat the Steelers in the postseason. Flacco also continued his streak of winning a game in his team's first round of the playoffs. His biggest accomplishment, however, may have been that he became the first quarterback in NFL history to start and win a playoff game in six of their first seven seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501030pit.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 3rd, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Divisional round of the playoffs, the Ravens traveled to Foxborough to take on the number-one seeded [[2014 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]], where they lost to the eventual Super Bowl champions in a 31\u201335 shootout, despite two back-to-back 14-point leads. Flacco still performed well, going 28/45 with 292 passing yards, a career-postseason-high 4 touchdown passes, 2 interceptions and a 92.1 passer rating. Once again, he didn't get sacked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots \u2013 January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor his efforts during the 2014 season, Flacco was invited to the  [[2015 Pro Bowl]] as an alternate but turned down the opportunity to play because his wife, Dana, was due to give birth to the couple's third child the same month.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zrebiec|first=Jeff|title=Joe Flacco declines chance to play in Sunday's Pro Bowl |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/ravens-insider/bal-joe-flacco-declines-pro-bowl-berth-20150120-story.html |date=January 20, 2015 | work=The Baltimore Sun | accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2015]], Flacco was ranked number 97, the lowest that he has ever been ranked, on the NFL's Top 100 Players list. He fell 39 spots from the previous year, where he was ranked number 58.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2015/0ap3000000491496/Top-100-Players-of-2015-No-97-Joe-Flacco |title='Top 100 Players of 2015': No. 97 Joe Flacco |publisher=National Football League  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n[[File:Flacco.jpg|thumb|272x272px|Flacco in 2015]]\nThe Ravens began their 2015 season in a road game against the [[2015 Denver Broncos|Denver Broncos]], the place where Flacco had his breakout playoff performance nearly three years earlier. Leading the game, 13\u20139, with less than a minute left in the third quarter, Flacco threw a pass down the middle of the field, aiming for Steve Smith Sr., but missed the pass terribly, as it was intercepted by Broncos cornerback [[Aqib Talib]] and returned 51 yards for a touchdown. It was Flacco's first pick-six since the [[2013 Baltimore Ravens season|2013 season finale]]. With less than a minute left in the game, the Ravens had the ball at the Denver 16-yard line and were trailing, 19\u201313. Flacco threw a pass into the end zone, intended for double-covered tight end [[Crockett Gillmore]], which was intercepted by safety, and former Raven, [[Darian Stewart]], officially ending the game for Baltimore.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130den.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Denver Broncos \u2013 September 13th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 2, against the [[2015 Oakland Raiders|Oakland Raiders]], Flacco bounced back by going 32-of-45 with 384 yards and two touchdown passes to Crockett Gillmore, with a 102.5 passer rating. However, while trying to rally the Ravens back at the end of the game, he was picked off by cornerback [[Neiko Thorpe]] with less than 30 seconds left, giving the Raiders a 37\u201333 upset win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200rai.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Oakland Raiders \u2013 September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> It was the first time in his NFL career that Flacco had started out a season with a 0\u20132 record.\n\nOn the final drive of the Ravens' Week 11 game versus the [[2015 St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]], Flacco suffered a torn ACL and MCL, ending his 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Flacco is out for season after tearing ACL in win|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000585381/article/joe-flacco-suffers-seasonending-knee-injury-in-win|publisher=National Football League|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> He stayed in the game to complete the drive and put Baltimore into a position to kick the game-winning field goal, giving the Ravens a 16\u201313 win at home.\n\nThe Ravens had a 3\u20137 record with Flacco at starting quarterback. Flacco finished the season with 266 completed passes out of 413 attempts, 2,791 yards, 14 touchdowns, 12 interceptions, an 83.1 passer rating, three rushing touchdowns and five fumbles, losing two.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlacJo00/gamelog/2015/ |title=Joe Flacco 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nOn March 2, 2016, Flacco agreed to a three-year extension to remain with the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14884034/baltimore-ravens-joe-flacco-reach-deal-extension |title=Joe Flacco gets 3-year extension with record $40M signing bonus | first=Jamison|last=Hensley|publisher=ESPN|date=March 2, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2016}}</ref> After their Week 3 victory against the [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Flacco and the Ravens had accrued a 3\u20130 record, their best record after three games since 2009, but the Ravens would struggle down the stretch, finishing with an 8\u20138 record and missing the playoffs for the second straight season, the first consecutive playoff misses for the franchise since 2004\u20132005. Flacco posted a career-high and franchise record 4,317 passing yards, the first time he reached at least 4,000 yards, but only threw 20 touchdowns and 15 interceptions, the second highest of his career. Flacco posted a 6.4 average per attempt, tying his career worst. Flacco also completed a career-high and franchise best 436 completions, and a career-high and franchise best 672 attempts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlacJo00/gamelog/2016 |title=Joe Flacco 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rav/2016.htm |title=2016 Baltimore Ravens Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The 672 pass attempts currently rank fifth most in a single season in league history.\n\n====2017 season====\nOn July 26, 2017, it was revealed that Flacco was diagnosed with a back injury, ruling him out for 3\u20136 weeks of training camp.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000822402/article/joe-flacco-back-preparing-to-sit-out-36-weeks |title=Joe Flacco (back) preparing to sit out 3\u20136 weeks |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=July 26, 2017 |publisher=National Football League |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref> During ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]] in Week 8, Flacco suffered a concussion after a hit from [[Kiko Alonso]]. Flacco left the game, and was relieved by [[Ryan Mallett]] for the rest. The Ravens nevertheless won 40\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000867728/article/joe-flacco-suffers-concussion-on-hit-from-kiko-alonso |title=Joe Flacco suffers concussion on hit from Kiko Alonso |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=October 26, 2017 |publisher=National Football League |access-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref> The Ravens finished the season with a 9\u20137 record and just missed the playoffs after losing 31\u201327 to the [[2017 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]] in Week 17, allowing the Buffalo Bills to qualify for the postseason. Flacco finished the season starting all 16 games, throwing for 3,141 yards and 18 touchdowns with 13 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlacJo00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Joe Flacco 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nOn September 9, 2018, Flacco threw for three touchdowns and had a passer rating of 121.7 in the season-opening blowout against the [[2018 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]] 47\u20133.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/baltimore-ravens/post/_/id/46068/td-party-joe-flacco-ravens-showing-the-world-their-new-targets |title=TD party: Joe Flacco, Ravens 'showing the world' their new targets |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=September 9, 2018 |access-date=September 19, 2019 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> The next week, on ''Thursday Night Football'', he recorded 376 yards and two touchdowns along with two interceptions against the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals|Cincinnati Bengals]], losing his seventh game in Cincinnati. He fumbled the ball in the fourth quarter, ending the chance for a comeback.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/baltimore-ravens/post/_/id/46211/joe-flacco-still-cant-shake-his-cincinnati-struggles |title=Joe Flacco still can't shake his Cincinnati struggles |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=September 14, 2018 |access-date=September 19, 2019 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref>\n\nAfter suffering a hip injury during a Week 9 loss to the [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/109654667-132.html |title=Ravens' Harbaugh on quarterback Joe Flacco hip injury |last=Richardson |first=Kevin |date=November 12, 2018 |website=Baltimore Sun |language=en-US |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> Flacco was replaced by rookie [[Lamar Jackson]] as the Ravens' starting quarterback.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25517134 |title=Ravens to stay with Jackson over healthy Flacco |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=December 12, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> Jackson performed well going 6\u20131 at the helm, and Flacco served in a backup role for the first time in his NFL career after he was cleared to play.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2018/12/12/ravens-lamar-jackson-starting-at-qb-joe-flacco-disappointed/ |title=Ravens Lamar Jackson Starting At QB, Joe Flacco \u2018Disappointed\u2019 |last=Viviano |first=Mark |date=December 12, 2018 |publisher=CBS Baltimore |access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> Overall, Flacco finished with 2,465 passing yards, 12 touchdowns, and six interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/ravens/john-harbaugh-expecting-joe-flaccos-practices-be-ramped-heading-week-14 |title=Harbaugh expecting Flacco's practices to be \"ramped up\" |last=Redmond |first=Lisa |date=December 5, 2018 |website=NBC Sports Washington |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> During the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: Los Angeles Chargers 23, Baltimore Ravens 17|Wild Card Round]] at home against the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers|Los Angeles Chargers]], which the Ravens trailing as much as 23\u20133 due to early struggles by Jackson, many fans chanted for Flacco to be brought on which never happened, while late in the fourth quarter, Jackson managed to make the game close in a 23\u201317 final loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/baltimore-ravens/post/_/id/48357 |title=In classy exit, Joe Flacco provides smooth handoff to Lamar Jackson |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=January 8, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Denver Broncos===\nOn February 13, 2019,  the Ravens agreed to trade Flacco to the [[Denver Broncos]] in exchange for their fourth-round pick in the [[2019 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001017780/article/broncos-agree-to-trade-for-ravens-qb-joe-flacco |title=Broncos agree to trade for Ravens QB Joe Flacco |last=Teope, Herbie |date=February 13, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The deal became official on March 13, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.denverbroncos.com/news/broncos-trade-for-quarterback-joe-flacco |title=Broncos trade for quarterback Joe Flacco |last=DiLalla |first=Aric |date=March 13, 2019 |website=DenverBroncos.com |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\n[[File:Joe Flacco.png|thumb|Flacco in a game against the [[Tennessee Titans]] ]]\nIn his Broncos debut, Flacco threw for 268 yards and a touchdown in a 16\u201324 road loss to the [[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128025 |title=Raiders beat Broncos 24-16 in 1st game after Brown's release |date=September 9, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |agency=Associated Press|access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> Flacco made his debut at [[Empower Field at Mile High]] in Week 2 against the [[2019 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]. In the game, Flacco threw for 292 yards, one touchdown, and one interception as the Broncos lost 16-14. With 31 seconds left in the game, Flacco threw a seven-yard touchdown pass and a two-point conversion both to wide receiver [[Emmanuel Sanders]] to take a 14-13 lead. However, the Bears quickly drove down the field and [[Eddy Pi\u00f1eiro]] kicked a 53-yard game winning field goal, spoiling Flacco's home debut.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128120 |title=Pineiro's 53-yard field goal lifts Bears past Broncos 16-14 |last=Stapleton |first=Arnie Melendrez |date=September 15, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4 against the [[2019 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Flacco threw for 303 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the 26-24 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128097 |title=Fournette leads Jags' 26-24 comeback over Broncos |date=September 29, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |agency=Associated Press|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref> In Week 5 against the [[2019 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]], Flacco threw for 182 yards, one touchdown, and one interception as the Broncos won their first game of the season by a score of 20-13.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128019 |title=Lindsay helps give Broncos' Fangio first win as coach |date=October 6, 2019 |website=www.espn.com|agency=Associated Press |access-date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> In Week 7 against the [[2019 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] on ''Thursday Night Football'', Flacco threw for 213 yards. During the game, Flacco was sacked a career high nine times in a single game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127902 |title=Patrick Mahomes hurts knee in Chiefs' win over Broncos |date=October 17, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref> In a Week 8 loss to the [[2019 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], Flacco threw for 174 yards in the 13-15 loss. In the game, he suffered a neck injury which prematurely ended his season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001071070/article/broncos-qb-joe-flacco-could-be-out-fivesix-weeks |title=Broncos QB Joe Flacco could be out five-six weeks |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=October 29, 2019 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.denverbroncos.com/news/broncos-placing-qb-joe-flacco-lb-corey-nelson-on-injured-reserve |title=Broncos placing QB Joe Flacco, LB Corey Nelson on injured reserve |last=DiLalla |first=Aric |date=November 1, 2019 |website=DenverBroncos.com |access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2020, the Broncos released Flacco with a failed physical designation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Broncos to release Joe Flacco after just one season |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106990/article/broncos-to-release-joe-flacco-after-just-one-season |publisher=NFL |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| [[List of Super Bowl champions|Won the Super Bowl]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:3em\"|\n| NFL record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e7e3e7;\"| Regular Season\n! colspan=\"9\" style=\"background:#e7e3e7;\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#e7e3e7;\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e7e3e7;\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! Season\n! Team\n! GP\n! GS\n! Comp\n! Att\n! Pct\n! Yds\n! YPA\n! Lg\n! TD\n! Int\n! Rate\n! Att\n! Yds\n! Avg\n! Lg\n! TD\n! Fum\n! Lost\n|-\n| [[2008 NFL season|2008]]\n| [[2008 Baltimore Ravens season|BAL]]\n| 16\n| 16\n| 257\n| 428\n| 60.0\n| 2,971\n| 6.9\n| 70\n| 14\n| 12\n| 80.3\n| '''52'''\n| '''180'''\n| 3.5\n| '''38'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n| 11\n| 2\n|-\n| [[2009 NFL season|2009]]\n| [[2009 Baltimore Ravens season|BAL]]\n| 16\n| 16\n| 315\n| 499\n| 63.1\n| 3,613\n| 7.2\n| 72\n| 21\n| 12\n| 88.9\n| 35\n| 56\n|