{"title_page": "Ichir\u014d Hatoyama", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Iichir\u014d Hatoyama}}\n{{Japanese name|Hatoyama}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ichir\u014d Hatoyama\n|native_name = {{nobold|\u9ce9\u5c71 \u4e00\u90ce}}\n|native_name_lang = ja\n|image       = Hatoyama_Ichir\u014d.jpg\n|imagesize   = 200px\n|office      = [[Prime Minister of Japan]]\n|monarch     = [[Hirohito|Sh\u014dwa]]\n|term_start  = 10 December 1954\n|term_end    = 23 December 1956\n|predecessor = [[Shigeru Yoshida]]\n|successor   = [[Tanzan Ishibashi]]\n|office1     = [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Member of the House of Representatives]]\n|term_start1 = 25 March 1915\n|term_end1   = 7 March 1959\n|predecessor1 = Masutar\u014d Takagi\n|successor1  = Seiichir\u014d Yasui\n|constituency1= [[Tokyo city district|Tokyo City]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1883|1|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Tokyo City]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1959|3|7|1883|1|1|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Bunky\u014d]], Japan\n|signature   = HatoyamaI kao.png\n|party       = [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic]] <small>(1955\u20131959)</small>\n|otherparty  = [[Rikken Seiy\u016bkai]] <small>(1915\u20131940)</small><br/>[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1945)|Japan Liberal Party]] <small>(1945\u20131948)</small><br/>{{nowrap|[[Democratic Liberal Party (Japan)|Democratic Liberal Party]] <small>(1948\u20131950)</small>}}<br/>[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1950)|Liberal Party]] <small>(1950\u20131953)</small><br/>[[Liberal Party\u2013Hatoyama]] <small>(1953)</small><br/>[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1950)|Liberal Party]]  <small>(1953)</small><br/>[[Democratic Party (Japan, 1954)|Japan Democratic Party]] <small>(1954\u20131955)</small>\n|spouse      = Kaoru\n|children    = [[Iichiro Hatoyama|Iichiro]] <br/> Yuriko <br/> Reiko <br/> Setsuko <br/> Keiko <br/> Nobuko\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Ichir\u014d Hatoyama'''|\u9ce9\u5c71 \u4e00\u90ce|Hatoyama Ichir\u014d|1 January 1883 \u2013 7 March 1959}} was a [[Japan]]ese [[politician]] who was [[Prime Minister of Japan]] from 1954 to 1956.<ref>Trumbull, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1955/11/15/archives/japans-rightists-will-unite-today-democrats-and-liberals-will-merge.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=22&st=cse  \"Japan's Rightists will Unite Today; Democrats and Liberals Will Merge \u2013 Present Premier Will Be Re-elected Nov. 22\"], ''The New York Times.'' 15 November 1955.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1956/12/20/archives/ishibashi-is-chosen-japanese-premier-ishibashi-chosen-japans.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=18&st=cse  \"Ishibashi Is Chosen Japanese Premier\"], ''The New York Times.'' 20 December 1956</ref><ref>Jorden, William J. [https://www.nytimes.com/1954/12/10/archives/hatoyama-named-premier-of-japan-brief-rule-seen-democrats-leader-is.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=5&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Named Premier of Japan; Brief Rule Seen; Democrats' Leader Is Chosen After Pledge to Socialists of Elections in Spring\"], ''The New York Times.'' 10 December 1954; [https://www.nytimes.com/1954/12/10/archives/hatoyama-reaches-lifelong-goal-that-twice-before-eluded-him.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=21&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Reaches Lifelong Goal That Twice Before Eluded Him; Premiership Denied Him First by Japan's Pre-War Militarists and Then by Allied Occupation Authorities\"], ''The New York Times.'' 10 December 1954.</ref><ref>Trumbull, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1955/02/28/archives/hatoyama-regime-victor-as-japan-elects-new-house-democratic-party.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=1&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Regime Victor as Japan Elects New House; Democratic Party Premier Due to Keep His Post \u2013 Poll Sets a Record; Hatoyama Leads in Japanese Vote\"],  ''The New York Times.'' 28 February 1955.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIchir\u014d Hatoyama was, [[Ichir\u014d|as his name indicates]], the first born boy. He was born into a wealthy cosmopolitan family in Tokyo. His father [[Kazuo Hatoyama]] (1856\u20131911) was a [[Yale Law School|Yale]] graduate (and Speaker of the House of Representatives) and his mother [[Haruko Hatoyama]] (1863\u20131938) was a famous author and the founder of [[Kyoritsu Women's University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/256876/Hatoyama-Ichiro|title=Hatoyama Ichiro (prime minister of Japan)|publisher=Britannica|date=7 March 1959|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref> His brother [[Hideo Hatoyama]] was a noted jurist.\n\nIchir\u014d<!-- It has been suggested that his article follow Japanese usage, with given name instead of surname as the short form. --> was a [[Master Mason]] and a [[Protestantism|Protestant Christian]] ([[Baptist]]). He was Japan's third postwar [[Christianity in Japan|Christian]] [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,807086-7,00.html|title=Land of the Reluctant Sparrows|publisher=TIME|date=14 March 1955|accessdate=29 August 2009}}; [https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/18/archives/tokyo-storm-center-ichiro-hatoyama-likes-hymnsinging.html?sq=Ichiro+hatoyama+Christian&scp=1&st=p  \"Tokyo Storm Center; Ichiro Hatoyama Likes Hymn-Singing\"], ''The New York Times.'' 18 October 1956.</ref>\n\n[[Iichir\u014d Hatoyama]], Ichir\u014d's only son, made a career for himself as a civil servant in the Budget Bureau of the [[Ministry of Finance (Japan)|Finance Ministry]]. Iichir\u014d retired after having achieved the rank of administrative Vice Minister.  In his second career in politics, he rose to become [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Foreign Minister of Japan]] in 1976\u20131977.<ref name=\"nyt1993\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/20/obituaries/iichiro-hatoyama-ex-foreign-minister-75.html  \"Iichiro Hatoyama; Ex-Foreign Minister, 75\" (obituary),] ''The New York Times.'' 20 December 1993.</ref>\n\nOne of Ichir\u014d's grandsons, [[Yukio Hatoyama]],  became prime minister in 2009 as a member of the [[Democratic Party of Japan]].\n\nIchir\u014d Hatoyama died in his Hatoyama Hall house, in Tokyo's [[Bunky\u014d]] district, on March 7, 1959. He was buried in the [[Yanaka Cemetery]], in nearly [[Tait\u014d]] district.\n\n==Political career==\nIchir\u014d was elected to the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] as a [[Rikken Seiy\u016bkai]] member in 1915. He was about to become prime minister in 1946, but was barred from politics for five years by [[Supreme Commander of the Allied Powers|Supreme Commander Allied Powers]] because they thought he had co-operated with the [[authoritarianism|authoritarian]] government in the 1930s and 1940s.<ref>Crane, Burton. [https://www.nytimes.com/1946/05/04/archives/hatoyama-barred-by-marthur-order-directive-forbidding-him-to-take.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=9&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Barred by MacArthur Order; Directive Forbidding Him to Take Diet Seat Rules Him Out as Japan's Premier\"], ''The New York Times.'' 4 May 1946; Crane, Burton. [https://www.nytimes.com/1946/05/05/archives/hatoyama-voices-surprise-at-order-challenges-ground-upon-which-he.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=11&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Voices Surprise at Order; Challenges Ground Upon Which He Is Barred From Holding Office in Japan\"], ''The New York Times.'' 5 May 1946.</ref> He was allowed to return in 1951. As prime minister in 1955, he rebuilt [[diplomatic ties]] with the [[Soviet Union]],<ref>Jorden, William J. [https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/18/archives/hatoyama-takes-plea-to-bulganin-return-of-some-isles-urged-at.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=26&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Takes Plea to Bulganin; Return of Some Isles Urged at Moscow Peace Parley --Treaty Reported Near Goodwill Aspect Stressed\"], ''The New York Times.'' 18 October 1956.</ref><ref name=odaka>{{cite web|last=Odaka|first=Konosuke|title=The Evolution of Social Policy in Japan|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/WBI/Resources/wbi37202.pdf|publisher=World Bank|accessdate=13 January 2013|year=2002}}</ref> and favored parole for some of the Class A war criminals who had been sentenced to life imprisonment by the [[Tokyo Trial]].<ref>Trumbull, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1955/06/21/archives/japan-urges-u-s-free-war-guilty-continued-appeals-are-based-largely.html?sq=Ichiro+hatoyama+parole&scp=1&st=p  \"Japan Urges U.S. Free War Guilty; Continued Appeals Are Based Largely on Dire Straits of Prisoners' Families\"], ''The New York Times.'' 21 June 1955.</ref>\n\n[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] files that were declassified in 2005 and then publicized in January 2007 by the [[National Archives and Records Administration|U.S. National Archives]] detail a plot by [[Uyoku dantai|ultranationalists]] to assassinate  prime minister [[Shigeru Yoshida]] and install a more hawkish government led by Ichir\u014d Hatoyama in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.military.com/NewsContent/0,13319,126978,00.html?ESRC=topstories.RSS|title=CIA Papers Reveal Japan Coup Plot |publisher=Military|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref> The plot was never carried out.\n\n== Hatoyama family and freemasonry ==\n[[File:Hatoyama family 1953.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kaoru Hatoyama|Kaoru]], Iichir\u014d, Ichir\u014d, and Yukio.]]\nIchir\u014d and some members of [[Hatoyama family]] are known as advocates of [[fraternity]]. During the [[Purge (During Occupation of Japan)|purge]] against Ichir\u014d (1946\u20131951), he received an English book ''The Totalitarian State against Man'' originally written in German by an Austrian [[freemason]] [[Richard von Coudenhove-Kalergi]] from a professor of [[Waseda University]] Kesaz\u014d Ichimura (1898\u20131950) who wanted Ichir\u014d to translate the English book into Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|date= 2004-09-10|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/shinbun/471.pdf|title= \u7b2c471\u53f7|format= PDF|work= Newsletter \"\u53cb\u611b\"|publisher= Yuai Association|quote= \u4eca\u671d\u8535\u306f\u3001\u300c\u3053\u306e\u672c\u306e\u7ffb\u8a33\u306f\u9ce9\u5c71\u4e00\u90ce\u3055\u3093\u306b\u3057\u3066\u8cb0\u304a\u3046\u3002 (\u4e2d\u7565) \u9ce9\u5c71\u3055\u3093\u306f\u5f80\u5e74\u306e\u512a\u7b49\u751f\u3060\u304b\u3089\u3001\u3053\u306e\u4f4d\u306e\u7ffb\u8a33\u8efd\u304f\u51fa\u6765\u308b\u3088\u3002\u6b74\u4ee3\u306e\u7dcf\u7406\u5927\u81e3\u3067\u3053\u308c\u3060\u3051\u306e\u672c\u3092\u51fa\u7248\u3057\u305f\u4eba\u306a\u3093\u3066\u8ab0\u3082\u3044\u306a\u3044\u3002\u305d\u306e\u65e5\u306e\u70ba\u306b\u3082\u3053\u306e\u7ffb\u8a33\u3092\u3057\u3066\u304a\u3044\u3066\u8cb0\u3044\u305f\u3044\u3093\u3060\u300d\u306a\u3069\u3068\u4e00\u5bf8\u304a\u3057\u3083\u3079\u308a\u3057\u3066\u96f2\u5834\u30f6\u6c60\u306e\u9ce9\u5c71\u5bb6\u306e\u5225\u8358\u306b\u81ea\u8ee2\u8eca\u3067\u51fa\u304b\u3051\u3066\u884c\u3063\u305f\u305d\u3046\u3067\u3042\u308b\u3002|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131017042940/http://yuaikyoukai.com/shinbun/471.pdf|archive-date= 17 October 2013|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The English book struck a sympathetic chord in Ichir\u014d, and he began to advocate fraternity, also known as y\u016bai (\u53cb\u611b) in Japanese.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hatoyama|first= Ichir\u014d|title= \u9ce9\u5c71\u4e00\u90ce\u56de\u9867\u9332|year= 1957|publisher= [[Bungeishunj\u016b]]|location= Tokyo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/katudo2006_douzou1.html|title= 2006\u5e748\u6708 \u9ce9\u5c71\u4e00\u90ce\u30fb\u85ab\u3054\u592b\u59bb\u9285\u9077\u5ea7\u5f0f|publisher= Yuai Association|quote= \u30af\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u30db\u30d5\u30ab\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc\u306e\u8457\u66f8\u306b\u5171\u9cf4\u81ea\u3089\u300c\u81ea\u7531\u3068\u4eba\u751f\u300d\u3068\u984c\u3057\u3066\u8a33\u51fa\u3057\u305f|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122807/http://yuaikyoukai.com/katudo2006_douzou1.html|archive-date= 26 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 1951, he was initiated as 1st [[Freemasonry#Degrees|degree of freemason]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Akama|first= G\u014d|title= \u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\u30e1\u30fc\u30bd\u30f3\u306e\u79d8\u5bc6 \u4e16\u754c\u6700\u5927\u306e\u7d50\u793e\u306e\u771f\u5b9f|year= 1983|publisher= San-ichi Publishing|location= Tokyo|page= 79}}</ref> and on March 26, 1955, passed as 2nd degree mason, and raised as 3rd degree mason.<ref>{{Cite web |author= Tim Wangelin|url= http://www2.gol.com/users/lodge1/history-e/papers/wangelin.html|title= Freemasonry and Modern Japanese History|work= Freemasonry in Japan|publisher= Far East Lodge No. 1|quote= On March 26, 1955, Ichiro Hatoyama and Yahachi Kawai, both Entered Apprentices (First Degree Masons), were made Fellowcrafts (Second Degeree Masons), and raised to Master Masons.|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= New Master Mason|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19550326&id=zFRIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hwAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=913,4699987|newspaper= [[Toledo Blade]]|date= March 26, 1955|accessdate= 2 May 2013|quote= TOKYO, March 26 (AP)&mdash;Prime Minister Ichiro Hatoyama became a master mason today.}}</ref>\n[[Image:Ichiro Hatoyama with two grandsons.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Ichir\u014d Hatoyama, [[Yukio Hatoyama]], and [[Kunio Hatoyama]].]]\nHis grandsons are advocates of fraternity. However, when a Japanese press asked Yukio Hatoyama's office and the [[List of Masonic Grand Lodges#Asia|masonic grand lodge of Japan]] whether Yukio Hatoyama was a freemason, his office denied it and the grand lodge of Japan didn't answer it.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/6278932/|title= \u9ce9\u5c71\u6c0f\u6539\u540d\u3068\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\u30e1\u30a4\u30bd\u30f3\u306e\u95a2\u4fc2\u5642\u306f\u300c\u4e8b\u5b9f\u7121\u6839\u300d\u3068\u4e8b\u52d9\u6240|author= Weeklypost|date= 2012-02-14|publisher= Livedoor news|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> At least, on his grandson [[Kunio Hatoyama]], the brother of Yukio, on a Japanese TV program ''Takajin no Money'' on August 25, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://tvtopic.goo.ne.jp/kansai/program/info/119890/index.html|title= \u305f\u304b\u3058\u3093NO\u30de\u30cd\u30fc|date= 2012-08-25|work= \u95a2\u897f\u7248TV\u30c8\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u691c\u7d22|publisher= tvtopic.[[goo (search engine)|goo]].ne.jp|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://archive.is/20130702215625/http://tvtopic.goo.ne.jp/kansai/program/info/119890/index.html|archive-date= 2 July 2013|df= dmy-all}}</ref> his partner [[Emily Hatoyama|Emily]]'s Australian father was a member of freemasonry. He said so, and said he had swum in a masonic pool with her at Tokyo when he had started to going steady with her.  Although he didn't say he himself was a mason or not, he insisted that he had not been invited to freemasonry, and he guessed his brother Yukio as a freemason.\n\nYukio and Kunio became the officers of a fraternal organization named ''Y\u016bai Ky\u014dkai'' (or ''Y\u016bai Association''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/english.html|title= Yuai Association|publisher= Yuai Association|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122803/http://yuaikyoukai.com/english.html|archive-date= 26 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref>) with their sister [[Kazuko Inoue|Kazuko]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/soshiki.html|title= \u5f79\u54e1|publisher= Yuai Association|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122805/http://yuaikyoukai.com/soshiki.html|archive-date= 26 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref> founded by their grandfather Ichir\u014d who became the first president of the former organization in 1953. And also Ichir\u014d's son Iichir\u014d became the third president of the same former organization.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/iichiro.html|title= 3\u4ee3\u76ee\u4f1a\u9577 \u9ce9\u5c71 \u5a01\u4e00\u90ce|publisher= Yuai Association|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131030071311/http://yuaikyoukai.com/iichiro.html|archive-date= 30 October 2013|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe granddaughter and two grandsons of Ichiro's founded a fraternal school ''Hatoyama Yuai-Jyuku'' at [[Hatoyama Hall]] (Hatoyama kaikan) on April 2008.<ref>[http://hatoyama-yuai-jyuku.com hatoyama-yuai-jyuku.com]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n''From the corresponding article in the Japanese Wikipedia''\n\n*Grand Cordon of the Order of the Chrysanthemum (1959; posthumous)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hatomander]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Itoh, Mayumi (2003). [https://books.google.com/books?id=EUMgpxv6MSEC ''The Hatoyama Dynasty: Japanese Political Leadership through the Generations'']. New York: Palgrave Macmillan. {{ISBN|1-403-96331-2}}, {{ISBN|978-1-403-96331-4}}. {{OCLC|248918078}}.\n* Saunavaara, Juha (28 September 2009).  [http://japanfocus.org/-Juha-Saunavaara/3229 \"Occupation Authorities, the Hatoyama Purge and the Making of Japan\u2019s Postwar Political Order\"]. ''The Asia-Pacific Journal'', Vol. 39-2-09.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Ichir\u014d Hatoyama}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6135682}}\n* ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' cover portrait of Ichir\u014d Hatoyama, [http://www.coverbrowser.com/covers/time/34  14 March 1955]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shigeru Yoshida]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Japan]]|years=1954\u20131956}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tanzan Ishibashi]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ry\u016bz\u014d Tanaka]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister of Education | years=1931\u20131934}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Makoto Sait\u014d]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Seiji Tsukamoto]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Cabinet Secretary]] | years=1927\u20131929}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Fujiya Suzuki]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Himself<br />[[Taketora Ogata]]<br />[[Bukichi Miki]]<br />[[Bamboku \u014cno]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|President of the Liberal Democratic Party]]|years= 1956}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tanzan Ishibashi]