{s-ttl|title=Representative for [[Tokyo's Tokyo city district]] (multi-member) | years=1915\u20131920|alongside=[[Bukichi Miki]], [[Keikichi Tanomogi]], numerous others}}\n{{s-non|reason=District eliminated}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Japan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hatoyama, Ichiro}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Prime Ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Education ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Hatoyama family|Ichiro]]\n[[Category:Japan Democratic Party (1954) politicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese Baptists]]\n[[Category:Japanese Christians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democratic Party (Japan) politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Japan, 1945) politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Rikken Seiy\u016bkai politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese politicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese Freemasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Iichir\u014d Hatoyama}}\n{{Japanese name|Hatoyama}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ichir\u014d Hatoyama\n|native_name = {{nobold|\u9ce9\u5c71 \u4e00\u90ce}}\n|native_name_lang = ja\n|image       = Hatoyama_Ichir\u014d.jpg\n|imagesize   = 200px\n|office      = [[Prime Minister of Japan]]\n|monarch     = [[Hirohito|Sh\u014dwa]]\n|term_start  = 10 December 1954\n|term_end    = 23 December 1956\n|predecessor = [[Shigeru Yoshida]]\n|successor   = [[Tanzan Ishibashi]]\n|office1     = [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Member of the House of Representatives]]\n|term_start1 = 25 March 1915\n|term_end1   = 7 March 1959\n|predecessor1 = Masutar\u014d Takagi\n|successor1  = Seiichir\u014d Yasui\n|constituency1= [[Tokyo city district|Tokyo City]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1883|1|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Tokyo City]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1959|3|7|1883|1|1|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Bunky\u014d]], [[Tokyo]], Japan\n|signature   = HatoyamaI kao.png\n|party       = [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] <small>(1955\u20131959)</small>\n|otherparty  = [[Rikken Seiy\u016bkai]] <small>(1915\u20131940)</small><br/>[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1945)|Japan Liberal Party]] <small>(1945\u20131948)</small><br/>{{nowrap|[[Democratic Liberal Party (Japan)|Democratic Liberal Party]] <small>(1948\u20131950)</small>}}<br/>[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1950)|Liberal Party]] <small>(1950\u20131953)</small><br/>[[Liberal Party\u2013Hatoyama]] <small>(1953)</small><br/>[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1950)|Liberal Party]]  <small>(1953)</small><br/>[[Democratic Party (Japan, 1954)|Japan Democratic Party]] <small>(1954\u20131955)</small>\n|spouse      = Kaoru\n|children    = [[Iichiro Hatoyama|Iichiro]] <br/> Yuriko <br/> Reiko <br/> Setsuko <br/> Keiko <br/> Nobuko\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Ichir\u014d Hatoyama'''|\u9ce9\u5c71 \u4e00\u90ce|Hatoyama Ichir\u014d|1 January 1883 \u2013 7 March 1959}} was a [[Japan]]ese [[politician]] who was [[Prime Minister of Japan]] from 1954 to 1956.<ref>Trumbull, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1955/11/15/archives/japans-rightists-will-unite-today-democrats-and-liberals-will-merge.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=22&st=cse  \"Japan's Rightists will Unite Today; Democrats and Liberals Will Merge \u2013 Present Premier Will Be Re-elected Nov. 22\"], ''The New York Times.'' 15 November 1955.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1956/12/20/archives/ishibashi-is-chosen-japanese-premier-ishibashi-chosen-japans.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=18&st=cse  \"Ishibashi Is Chosen Japanese Premier\"], ''The New York Times.'' 20 December 1956</ref><ref>Jorden, William J. [https://www.nytimes.com/1954/12/10/archives/hatoyama-named-premier-of-japan-brief-rule-seen-democrats-leader-is.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=5&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Named Premier of Japan; Brief Rule Seen; Democrats' Leader Is Chosen After Pledge to Socialists of Elections in Spring\"], ''The New York Times.'' 10 December 1954; [https://www.nytimes.com/1954/12/10/archives/hatoyama-reaches-lifelong-goal-that-twice-before-eluded-him.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=21&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Reaches Lifelong Goal That Twice Before Eluded Him; Premiership Denied Him First by Japan's Pre-War Militarists and Then by Allied Occupation Authorities\"], ''The New York Times.'' 10 December 1954.</ref><ref>Trumbull, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1955/02/28/archives/hatoyama-regime-victor-as-japan-elects-new-house-democratic-party.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=1&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Regime Victor as Japan Elects New House; Democratic Party Premier Due to Keep His Post \u2013 Poll Sets a Record; Hatoyama Leads in Japanese Vote\"],  ''The New York Times.'' 28 February 1955.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIchir\u014d Hatoyama was, [[Ichir\u014d|as his name indicates]], the first born boy. He was born into a wealthy cosmopolitan family in Tokyo. His father [[Kazuo Hatoyama]] (1856\u20131911) was a [[Yale Law School|Yale]] graduate (and Speaker of the House of Representatives) and his mother [[Haruko Hatoyama]] (1863\u20131938) was a famous author and the founder of [[Kyoritsu Women's University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/256876/Hatoyama-Ichiro|title=Hatoyama Ichiro (prime minister of Japan)|publisher=Britannica|date=7 March 1959|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref> His brother [[Hideo Hatoyama]] was a noted jurist.\n\nIchir\u014d<!-- It has been suggested that his article follow Japanese usage, with given name instead of surname as the short form. --> was a [[Master Mason]] and a [[Protestantism|Protestant Christian]] ([[Baptist]]). He was Japan's third postwar [[Christianity in Japan|Christian]] [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,807086-7,00.html|title=Land of the Reluctant Sparrows|publisher=TIME|date=14 March 1955|accessdate=29 August 2009}}; [https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/18/archives/tokyo-storm-center-ichiro-hatoyama-likes-hymnsinging.html?sq=Ichiro+hatoyama+Christian&scp=1&st=p  \"Tokyo Storm Center; Ichiro Hatoyama Likes Hymn-Singing\"], ''The New York Times.'' 18 October 1956.</ref>\n\n[[Iichir\u014d Hatoyama]], Ichir\u014d's only son, made a career for himself as a civil servant in the Budget Bureau of the [[Ministry of Finance (Japan)|Finance Ministry]]. Iichir\u014d retired after having achieved the rank of administrative Vice Minister.  In his second career in politics, he rose to become [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Foreign Minister of Japan]] in 1976\u20131977.<ref name=\"nyt1993\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/20/obituaries/iichiro-hatoyama-ex-foreign-minister-75.html  \"Iichiro Hatoyama; Ex-Foreign Minister, 75\" (obituary),] ''The New York Times.'' 20 December 1993.</ref>\n\nOne of Ichir\u014d's grandsons, [[Yukio Hatoyama]],  became prime minister in 2009 as a member of the [[Democratic Party of Japan]].\n\nIchir\u014d Hatoyama died in his Hatoyama Hall house, in Tokyo's [[Bunky\u014d]] district, on March 7, 1959. He was buried in the [[Yanaka Cemetery]], in nearly [[Tait\u014d]] district.\n\n==Political career==\nIchir\u014d was elected to the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] as a [[Rikken Seiy\u016bkai]] member in 1915. He was about to become prime minister in 1946, but was barred from politics for five years by [[Supreme Commander of the Allied Powers|Supreme Commander Allied Powers]] because they thought he had co-operated with the [[authoritarianism|authoritarian]] government in the 1930s and 1940s.<ref>Crane, Burton. [https://www.nytimes.com/1946/05/04/archives/hatoyama-barred-by-marthur-order-directive-forbidding-him-to-take.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=9&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Barred by MacArthur Order; Directive Forbidding Him to Take Diet Seat Rules Him Out as Japan's Premier\"], ''The New York Times.'' 4 May 1946; Crane, Burton. [https://www.nytimes.com/1946/05/05/archives/hatoyama-voices-surprise-at-order-challenges-ground-upon-which-he.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=11&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Voices Surprise at Order; Challenges Ground Upon Which He Is Barred From Holding Office in Japan\"], ''The New York Times.'' 5 May 1946.</ref> He was allowed to return in 1951. As prime minister in 1955, he rebuilt [[diplomatic ties]] with the [[Soviet Union]],<ref>Jorden, William J. [https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/18/archives/hatoyama-takes-plea-to-bulganin-return-of-some-isles-urged-at.html?sq=Ichiro%2520hatoyama&scp=26&st=cse  \"Hatoyama Takes Plea to Bulganin; Return of Some Isles Urged at Moscow Peace Parley --Treaty Reported Near Goodwill Aspect Stressed\"], ''The New York Times.'' 18 October 1956.</ref><ref name=odaka>{{cite web|last=Odaka|first=Konosuke|title=The Evolution of Social Policy in Japan|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/WBI/Resources/wbi37202.pdf|publisher=World Bank|accessdate=13 January 2013|year=2002}}</ref> and favored parole for some of the Class A war criminals who had been sentenced to life imprisonment by the [[Tokyo Trial]].<ref>Trumbull, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1955/06/21/archives/japan-urges-u-s-free-war-guilty-continued-appeals-are-based-largely.html?sq=Ichiro+hatoyama+parole&scp=1&st=p  \"Japan Urges U.S. Free War Guilty; Continued Appeals Are Based Largely on Dire Straits of Prisoners' Families\"], ''The New York Times.'' 21 June 1955.</ref>\n\n[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] files that were declassified in 2005 and then publicized in January 2007 by the [[National Archives and Records Administration|U.S. National Archives]] detail a plot by [[Uyoku dantai|ultranationalists]] to assassinate  prime minister [[Shigeru Yoshida]] and install a more hawkish government led by Ichir\u014d Hatoyama in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.military.com/NewsContent/0,13319,126978,00.html?ESRC=topstories.RSS|title=CIA Papers Reveal Japan Coup Plot |publisher=Military|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref> The plot was never carried out.\n\n== Hatoyama family and freemasonry ==\n[[File:Hatoyama family 1953.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kaoru Hatoyama|Kaoru]], Iichir\u014d, Ichir\u014d, and Yukio.]]\nIchir\u014d and some members of [[Hatoyama family]] are known as advocates of [[fraternity]]. During the [[Purge (During Occupation of Japan)|purge]] against Ichir\u014d (1946\u20131951), he received an English book ''The Totalitarian State against Man'' originally written in German by an Austrian [[freemason]] [[Richard von Coudenhove-Kalergi]] from a professor of [[Waseda University]] Kesaz\u014d Ichimura (1898\u20131950) who wanted Ichir\u014d to translate the English book into Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|date= 2004-09-10|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/shinbun/471.pdf|title= \u7b2c471\u53f7|format= PDF|work= Newsletter \"\u53cb\u611b\"|publisher= Yuai Association|quote= \u4eca\u671d\u8535\u306f\u3001\u300c\u3053\u306e\u672c\u306e\u7ffb\u8a33\u306f\u9ce9\u5c71\u4e00\u90ce\u3055\u3093\u306b\u3057\u3066\u8cb0\u304a\u3046\u3002 (\u4e2d\u7565) \u9ce9\u5c71\u3055\u3093\u306f\u5f80\u5e74\u306e\u512a\u7b49\u751f\u3060\u304b\u3089\u3001\u3053\u306e\u4f4d\u306e\u7ffb\u8a33\u8efd\u304f\u51fa\u6765\u308b\u3088\u3002\u6b74\u4ee3\u306e\u7dcf\u7406\u5927\u81e3\u3067\u3053\u308c\u3060\u3051\u306e\u672c\u3092\u51fa\u7248\u3057\u305f\u4eba\u306a\u3093\u3066\u8ab0\u3082\u3044\u306a\u3044\u3002\u305d\u306e\u65e5\u306e\u70ba\u306b\u3082\u3053\u306e\u7ffb\u8a33\u3092\u3057\u3066\u304a\u3044\u3066\u8cb0\u3044\u305f\u3044\u3093\u3060\u300d\u306a\u3069\u3068\u4e00\u5bf8\u304a\u3057\u3083\u3079\u308a\u3057\u3066\u96f2\u5834\u30f6\u6c60\u306e\u9ce9\u5c71\u5bb6\u306e\u5225\u8358\u306b\u81ea\u8ee2\u8eca\u3067\u51fa\u304b\u3051\u3066\u884c\u3063\u305f\u305d\u3046\u3067\u3042\u308b\u3002|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131017042940/http://yuaikyoukai.com/shinbun/471.pdf|archive-date= 17 October 2013|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The English book struck a sympathetic chord in Ichir\u014d, and he began to advocate fraternity, also known as y\u016bai (\u53cb\u611b) in Japanese.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hatoyama|first= Ichir\u014d|title= \u9ce9\u5c71\u4e00\u90ce\u56de\u9867\u9332|year= 1957|publisher= [[Bungeishunj\u016b]]|location= Tokyo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/katudo2006_douzou1.html|title= 2006\u5e748\u6708 \u9ce9\u5c71\u4e00\u90ce\u30fb\u85ab\u3054\u592b\u59bb\u9285\u9077\u5ea7\u5f0f|publisher= Yuai Association|quote= \u30af\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u30db\u30d5\u30ab\u30ec\u30eb\u30ae\u30fc\u306e\u8457\u66f8\u306b\u5171\u9cf4\u81ea\u3089\u300c\u81ea\u7531\u3068\u4eba\u751f\u300d\u3068\u984c\u3057\u3066\u8a33\u51fa\u3057\u305f|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122807/http://yuaikyoukai.com/katudo2006_douzou1.html|archive-date= 26 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 1951, he was initiated as 1st [[Freemasonry#Degrees|degree of freemason]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Akama|first= G\u014d|title= \u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\u30e1\u30fc\u30bd\u30f3\u306e\u79d8\u5bc6 \u4e16\u754c\u6700\u5927\u306e\u7d50\u793e\u306e\u771f\u5b9f|year= 1983|publisher= San-ichi Publishing|location= Tokyo|page= 79}}</ref> and on March 26, 1955, passed as 2nd degree mason, and raised as 3rd degree mason.<ref>{{Cite web |author= Tim Wangelin|url= http://www2.gol.com/users/lodge1/history-e/papers/wangelin.html|title= Freemasonry and Modern Japanese History|work= Freemasonry in Japan|publisher= Far East Lodge No. 1|quote= On March 26, 1955, Ichiro Hatoyama and Yahachi Kawai, both Entered Apprentices (First Degree Masons), were made Fellowcrafts (Second Degeree Masons), and raised to Master Masons.|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= New Master Mason|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19550326&id=zFRIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hwAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=913,4699987|newspaper= [[Toledo Blade]]|date= March 26, 1955|accessdate= 2 May 2013|quote= TOKYO, March 26 (AP)&mdash;Prime Minister Ichiro Hatoyama became a master mason today.}}</ref>\n[[Image:Ichiro Hatoyama with two grandsons.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Ichir\u014d Hatoyama, [[Yukio Hatoyama]], and [[Kunio Hatoyama]].]]\nHis grandsons are advocates of fraternity. However, when a Japanese press asked Yukio Hatoyama's office and the [[List of Masonic Grand Lodges#Asia|masonic grand lodge of Japan]] whether Yukio Hatoyama was a freemason, his office denied it and the grand lodge of Japan didn't answer it.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/6278932/|title= \u9ce9\u5c71\u6c0f\u6539\u540d\u3068\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\u30e1\u30a4\u30bd\u30f3\u306e\u95a2\u4fc2\u5642\u306f\u300c\u4e8b\u5b9f\u7121\u6839\u300d\u3068\u4e8b\u52d9\u6240|author= Weeklypost|date= 2012-02-14|publisher= Livedoor news|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> At least, on his grandson [[Kunio Hatoyama]], the brother of Yukio, on a Japanese TV program ''Takajin no Money'' on August 25, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://tvtopic.goo.ne.jp/kansai/program/info/119890/index.html|title= \u305f\u304b\u3058\u3093NO\u30de\u30cd\u30fc|date= 2012-08-25|work= \u95a2\u897f\u7248TV\u30c8\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u691c\u7d22|publisher= tvtopic.[[goo (search engine)|goo]].ne.jp|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://archive.is/20130702215625/http://tvtopic.goo.ne.jp/kansai/program/info/119890/index.html|archive-date= 2 July 2013|df= dmy-all}}</ref> his partner [[Emily Hatoyama|Emily]]'s Australian father was a member of freemasonry. He said so, and said he had swum in a masonic pool with her at Tokyo when he had started to going steady with her.  Although he didn't say he himself was a mason or not, he insisted that he had not been invited to freemasonry, and he guessed his brother Yukio as a freemason.\n\nYukio and Kunio became the officers of a fraternal organization named ''Y\u016bai Ky\u014dkai'' (or ''Y\u016bai Association''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/english.html|title= Yuai Association|publisher= Yuai Association|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122803/http://yuaikyoukai.com/english.html|archive-date= 26 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref>) with their sister [[Kazuko Inoue|Kazuko]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/soshiki.html|title= \u5f79\u54e1|publisher= Yuai Association|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140826122805/http://yuaikyoukai.com/soshiki.html|archive-date= 26 August 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref> founded by their grandfather Ichir\u014d who became the first president of the former organization in 1953. And also Ichir\u014d's son Iichir\u014d became the third president of the same former organization.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://yuaikyoukai.com/iichiro.html|title= 3\u4ee3\u76ee\u4f1a\u9577 \u9ce9\u5c71 \u5a01\u4e00\u90ce|publisher= Yuai Association|access-date= 2 May 2013|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131030071311/http://yuaikyoukai.com/iichiro.html|archive-date= 30 October 2013|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe granddaughter and two grandsons of Ichiro's founded a fraternal school ''Hatoyama Yuai-Jyuku'' at [[Hatoyama Hall]] (Hatoyama kaikan) on April 2008.<ref>[http://hatoyama-yuai-jyuku.com hatoyama-yuai-jyuku.com]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n''From the corresponding article in the Japanese Wikipedia''\n\n*Grand Cordon of the Order of the Chrysanthemum (1959; posthumous)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hatomander]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Itoh, Mayumi (2003). [https://books.google.com/books?id=EUMgpxv6MSEC ''The Hatoyama Dynasty: Japanese Political Leadership through the Generations'']. New York: Palgrave Macmillan. {{ISBN|1-403-96331-2}}, {{ISBN|978-1-403-96331-4}}. {{OCLC|248918078}}.\n* Saunavaara, Juha (28 September 2009).  [http://japanfocus.org/-Juha-Saunavaara/3229 \"Occupation Authorities, the Hatoyama Purge and the Making of Japan\u2019s Postwar Political Order\"]. ''The Asia-Pacific Journal'', Vol. 39-2-09.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Ichir\u014d Hatoyama}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6135682}}\n* ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' cover portrait of Ichir\u014d Hatoyama, [http://www.coverbrowser.com/covers/time/34  14 March 1955]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Shigeru Yoshida]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Japan]]|years=1954\u20131956}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tanzan Ishibashi]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ry\u016bz\u014d Tanaka]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister of Education | years=1931\u20131934}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Makoto Sait\u014d]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Seiji Tsukamoto]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Cabinet Secretary]] | years=1927\u20131929}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Fujiya Suzuki]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Himself<br />[[Taketora Ogata]]<br />[[Bukichi Miki]]<br />[[Bamboku \u014cno]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|President of the Liberal Democratic Party]]|years= 1956}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tanzan Ishibashi]]}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|President of the Liberal Democratic Party]]|alongside=[[Taketora Ogata]], [[Bukichi Miki]], [[Bamboku \u014cno]]|years=1955\u20131956}}\n{{s-aft|after=Himself}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Japan Democratic Party (1954)|President of the Japan Democratic Party]]|years= 1954\u20131955}}\n{{s-non|reason=\"conservative merger\" with Liberal Party}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party (Japan, 1945)|President of the Liberal Party]]|years= 1945\u20131946 (purged)}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Shigeru Yoshida]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Suzuki Kisabur\u014d|Kisabur\u014d Suzuki]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Acting President of [[Rikken Seiy\u016bkai]]|alongside=[[Yonez\u014d Maeda]], [[Toshio Shimada]], [[Chikuhei Nakajima]]|years= 1937\u20131939}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Fusanosuke Kuhara]]<br />[[Chikuhei Nakajima]]}}\n{{s-par|jp-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sanz\u014d Nosaka]]<br />...}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Representative for [[Tokyo's 1st district (1947\u20131993)|Tokyo's 1st district]] (multi-member) | years=1952\u20131959|alongside=[[Inejir\u014d Asanuma]], several others}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seiichir\u014d Yasui]]<br/>...}}\n{{s-new|reason=New constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Representative for [[Tokyo's 1st district (1946)|Tokyo's 1st district]] (multi-member) | years=1946\u20131946 (purged)/1947|alongside=[[Inejir\u014d Asanuma]], [[Sanz\u014d Nosaka]] numerous others}}\n{{s-non|reason=District eliminated}}\n{{s-new|reason=New constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Representative for [[Tokyo's 2nd district (1928-1942)|Tokyo's 2nd district]] (multi-member) | years=1928\u20131943 (retired)/1946|alongside=[[Isoo Abe]], [[Takeru Inukai]], numerous others}}\n{{s-non|reason=District eliminated}}\n{{s-new|reason=New constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Representative for [[Tokyo's 10th district (1920\u20131924)|Tokyo's 10th district]] | years=1920\u20131928}}\n{{s-non|reason=District eliminated}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Masutar\u014d Takagi]]<br />...}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Representative for [[Tokyo's Tokyo city district]] (multi-member) | years=1915\u20131920|alongside=[[Bukichi Miki]], [[Keikichi Tanomogi]], numerous others}}\n{{s-non|reason=District eliminated}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Japan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hatoyama, Ichiro}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Prime Ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Education ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Hatoyama family|Ichiro]]\n[[Category:Japan Democratic Party (1954) politicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese Baptists]]\n[[Category:Japanese Christians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democratic Party (Japan) politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Japan, 1945) politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Rikken Seiy\u016bkai politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese politicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese Freemasons]]\n", "name_user": "Illegitimate Barrister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ichir%C5%8D_Hatoyama"}
{"title_page": "Amos Gitai", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli film director and screenwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Amos portrait 1.jpg\n| name         = Amos Gitai\n| caption      = Gitai in 2008\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1950|10|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Haifa]], Israel\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Filmmaker\n*author}}\n| alma_mater   = {{Unbulleted list|[[Technion]]|[[University of California, Berkeley]]}}\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Rivka Gitai|1980}}\n| parents      = [[Munio Weinraub]]\n| children     =\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| website      = {{URL|amosgitai.com}}\n}}\n\nAmos Gitai (born 11 October 1950) is an Israeli filmmaker, based between Haifa and Paris. \nGitai's work was presented in several major retrospectives in Pompidou Center Paris, the Museum of Modern Art (MoMA) New York, Lincoln Center New York, and the British Film Institute London. To date Amos Gitai has created over 90 works of art throughout 40 years. His films were presented in the Cannes Film Festival for the Palme d'Or as well as The Venice International Film Festival for the Golden Lion award.[citation needed] \nHe has worked with Juliette Binoche, Jeanne Moreau, Natalie Portman, Yael Abecassis, Samuel Fuller, Hanna Schygulla, Annie Lennox, Barbara Hendricks, L\u00e9a Seydoux, Valeria Bruni Tedeschi, Henri Alekan, Renato Berta, Nurith Aviv, \u00c9ric Gautier and more. \nSince 2000 he has been collaborating with the French screenwriter Marie-Jos\u00e9 Sanselme. He received several prestigious prizes, such as the Leopard of Honor at the Locarno International Film Festival (2008), the Roberto Rossellini prize (2005), the Robert Bresson prize (2013), the Paradjanov prize (2014), and L\u00e9gion d'Honneur (2017). In 2018, Amos Gitai has been elected professor at the chair of artistic creation at the Coll\u00e8ge de France, with a series of 12 lessons on cinema.\n\n\n==Early life==\nGitai was born to [[Munio Weinraub]] (Gitai), an architect formed at the [[Interbellum|pre-war]] German [[Bauhaus]] art school, and to [[Efratia Margalit]], an intellectual, storyteller and a teacher.<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmfestivals.com/cannes99/html/seloff4.htm |title=Film Festival : Cannes 99 |publisher=Filmfestivals.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629183721/http://www.filmfestivals.com/cannes99/html/seloff4.htm |archivedate=29 June 2011 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |url= http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=5&lang=1 |title= Conversation Amos Gitai / Peter Cowie|work=Amos Gitai official homepage |accessdate=26 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215071253/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=5&lang=1|archivedate=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"IMDb\">{{IMDb name|0321159}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=60&lang=1 |title=Munio Weinraub Gitai Architect (1909-1970) &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091015183905/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=60&lang=1|archivedate=15 October 2009}}</ref> He holds a degree in Architecture from the [[Technion]] in Haifa and a PhD in Architecture from the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. \n\nIn 1973, during the [[Yom Kippur War]], Gitai had to interrupt his architecture studies as he was called up to reserve service as part of a helicopter rescue crew. While serving, he shot 8mm footage of the fighting, and said this served as his entry into the world of film making.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=2&lang=1 |title=Biography &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707135035/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=2&lang=1| archivedate= 7 July 2011 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\n\n===Trilogies===\n[[File:Amos Gitai Jeanne Moreau.jpg|thumb|Amos Gitai and [[Jeanne Moreau]] at the ''One day you'll understand'' shooting, (2008)]]\nGitai began his career directing mostly documentaries. In 1980 he directed his first full-length Israeli film, Home (1980), the first part of the House Trilogy: ''Home'' (1980) ''A House in Jerusalem'' (1998), ''News from Home / News from House'' (2005). The film follows a house in West Jerusalem, abandoned during the 1948 war by its Palestinian owner. It was rejected and was censored by Israeli television; however, it was screened at the Berlin and the Rotterdam International Film Festivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=36&lang=0 |title=House / La Maison &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328095650/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=36&lang=0|archivedate=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHouse was the first trilogy of many others; a concept Gitai consistently worked with during his career, offering a complex and layered view on the Geo-political Israeli reality.\n\n\"Gita\u00ef wants this house to be both a symbol and something very concrete; he wants it to become a character in a film. He achieves one of the most beautiful things a camera can register 'live', as it were; people who look at the same thing but see different things - and who are moved by that vision. In this crumbling shell of a house, real hallucinations begin to take shape. The film's central idea is simple and the film has simply the force of that idea, no more, no less.\" (Serge Daney, Lib\u00e9ration, 1 March 1982)\n\nWadi (''Wadi'' 1981, ''Wadi Ten Years After'' 1991, ''Wadi Grand Canyon'' 2001), similar to House is dealing with a specific location and examines the complex relationships between the residents of the former stone quarry: Eastern European immigrants, survivors of the camps and Arabs who have also been expelled from their homes. Gitai turns the valley into a symbol of a possible coexistence.<ref>http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=39&lang=1</ref>\n \nIn 1982 he directed \"Field Diary\" (1982). A film-diary shot in the occupied territories before and during the invasion of Lebanon and, creating a controversy and leading to Gitai leaving Israel for France (1983-1993).<ref>{{cite web|author=Ramesh Jaura |url=http://www.indepthnews.net/news/news.php?key1=2011-05-10%2018:28:47&key2=1 |title=IDN-InDepthNews &#124; Analysis That Matters |publisher=Indepthnews.net |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=15 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331005249/http://www.indepthnews.net/news/news.php?key1=2011-05-10%2018%3A28%3A47&key2=1 |archivedate=31 March 2012 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\"'Field Diary\u201d offers a civilian image of war, [\u2026] setting it apart from the rest of audio-visual production by its content as much as by its mode of operation, by the solution it offers to a problem that pertains to the ethics of the filmmaker as much as to the aesthetics of cinema\" (Yann Lardeau, \"Une \u00e9thique du travelling\", Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, n\u00b0344, February 1983).\n\nGitai created as well fiction trilogies. The \"Exile Trilogy\" composed of ''[[Esther (1986 film)|Esther]]'', 1985 that tells the Old Testament story of Esther, who does not know she is Jewish when she is chosen by King Ashasuerus as his wife and was presented at the International Critics\u2019 Week of the [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n<ref>\nStephen Holden (19 May 1989).\n[https://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/19/movies/reviews-film-the-purim-story-with-modern-overtones.html Reviews/Film; The Purim Story, With Modern Overtones]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.\n</ref>\n''Berlin-J\u00e9rusalem'', 1989 was based on the biographies of the German expressionist poet, [[Else Lasker-Sch\u00fcler]], and the Russian Zionist, [[Mania Shohat]], and their respective itineraries towards the mythical Jerusalem of the 1930s.<ref>Fred Camper, \"Face to Face With History\", ''Chicago Reader'', 1989</ref><ref>Mansel Stimpson, \"Amos Gitai Branches Out\", ''What's on in London'', 6 March 1991</ref> The film competed in the [[46th Venice International Film Festival]] and won first prize at the [[Istanbul Festival]]. leading actresses:\n[[Lisa Kreuzer]], [[Rivka Neumann]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=46&lang=1 |title=Berlin-Jerusalem &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328095654/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=46&lang=1|archivedate=28 March 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Golem, the Spirit of the Exile]]'', 1991 which explores the contemporary meanings of the Book of Ruth in the Bible.<ref>http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=48&lang=1</ref>\n\n\"The director holds the story at an analytical distance. Events are re-enacted in a sequence of ritual tableaux shot in the ruins of Wadi Salib, the old Arab neighbourhood of Haifa that the Palestinians abandoned after the 1948 war. The sense of ancient unsettled scores that have simmered for centuries is almost palpable in this beautiful but ravaged territory. In the most striking shots, the actors seem to blend into the architecture like the figures in Persian miniatures. These shots are pointedly contrasted with others photographed in the same vicinity, which make it look like a squalid contemporary junkyard. The juxtapositions suggest how overwhelmingly the region's history continues to haunt Israel's present.\" (Stephen Holden, ''The New York Times'', 19 May 1989)\n\n[[File:Gitai88.jpg|thumb|250px|Amos Gitai and [[Henri Alekan]], shooting Esther, 1986.]]\n\nThe \"City Trilogy\" (''[[Devarim (film)|Devarim]]'', 1995 ; ''[[Yom Yom]]'', 1998 ; ''[[Kadosh]]'', 1999), was created after Gitai's return to Israel in 1993, after [[Yitzhak Rabin]]\u2019s victory in the elections and the [[Oslo Accords]]. Each film is dedicated to a different city in Israel: \"Devarim\" takes place in Tel Aviv, and is after the novel by Yaakov Shabtai, Past Continuous. The film depicts the spiritual disarray of three men in their thirties and forties, in the agitation and turmoil of Tel Aviv, the city created by Jewish pioneers in 1909. None of them has the life he had imagined. \"Yom Yom\" draws upon Haifa's tradition of peaceful coexistence between Arab and Jewish neighbours to tell a dark comic tale of characters driven by divided loyalties and neurotic inhibitions. Leslie Camhi wrote \"Gita\u00ef\u2019s genius is to show the conflict infiltrating every encounter, from the marketplace to the bedroom and beyond; the vivid portraits of Israeli social types, whether arrogant reservists or hapless nebbishes, stand in sharp contrast to images promoted in the media.\" (Leslie Camhi, Village Voice, 20 February 2001). \n''[[Kadosh]]'' is set in [[Mea Shearim]], the ultra-orthodox neighbourhood of Jerusalem and tells the story of Me\u00efr and Rivka, that have been married for ten years but have to divorce because they have no children. Actors: [[Yael Abecassis]], Samuel Calderon, [[Lea Koenig]], [[Yussuf Abu-Warda]], Uri Klauzner, [[Rivka Michaeli]], Yoram Hattab.\n<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C06E6D81531F935A25751C0A9669C8B63</ref>\nThe review in ''The Wall Street Journal'':\n''Kadosh'' - \"the title means \"sacred\" - addresses universal themes. Among them are the demands of ultra-orthodox religion, which confines as it sustains, and the suffering of men and women whose religion comes before love, but whose culture lacks a vocabulary for expressing personal pain. Yet Kadosh is also foreign in the extreme, an austere and shocking portrait of daily life in Mea Shearim, the Hasidic Jewish quarter of Jerusalem. ( ... ) Kadosh is a horror story, or rather two horror stories intertwined, about women tyrannised by men in the name of religious belief.\"\n(The Wall Street Journal, 17 March 2000)\n\"Kadosh\" was entered into the [[1999 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>[http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/kadosh Kadosh in 1999 Cannes Film Festival]</ref>\n\nAnother fiction trilogy deals with important historical events in Israel: ''[[Kippur]]'', 2000; ''[[Eden (2001 film)|Eden]]'', 2001; ''[[Kedma (film)|Kedma]]'', 2002.\n''Kippur''  (2000) was Israel's first large-scale cinematic depiction of the considerably difficult and traumatic [[Yom Kippur War]] of 1973. Critics praised its absence of sensationalism and its unsentimental depiction of war.<ref>{{cite web|author= TV Guide Network New |url=http://movies.tvguide.com/kippur/review/134913 |title=Kippur Review |publisher=Movies.tvguide.com |date= |accessdate=2 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528021917/http://movies.tvguide.com/kippur/review/134913|archivedate=28 May 2012}}</ref>\nCharles Tesson wrote in ''Les Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma'': \"Throughout the film, the viewer remains locked in this absurd question: are we in the war or is that happening somewhere else, off-screen, or was it happening just before the camera got there? We never know for certain and then we realise that this uncertainty is in fact the most profound truth of war, as cinema has hardly ever shown it, with a force and an intensity that takes your breath away. [\u2026] The principle for filming warfare in Kippur is simple, limpid. Favouring real time spaces, [\u2026] making the camera an extra person walking with the soldiers, running behind the others to get on the helicopter before it takes off. The viewer is inside the war while remaining outside the group, accompanying them. Never does the film encourage in the viewer that fantasy of being one of them.\" (Charles Tesson, Les Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma, n\u00b0549, September 2000).\n''Kippur'' was entered into the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]] starring Liron Levo, Tomer Russo, Uri Klauzner, Yoram Hattab and [[Juliano Mer-Khamis]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/5157/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Kippur |accessdate=2009-10-10|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> \n''Eden'' competed in the Venice Biennale 2001.<ref>\n[http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=69&lang=1 Eden on Amos Gitai site] \n</ref> \n''Kedma'' was entered into the [[2002 Cannes Film Festival]]. Its leading actors are Andrei Kashkar and Helena Yaralova. \n<ref>\n[http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/kedma \"Festival de Cannes: Kedma\"]. festival-cannes.com.\n</ref>\n\nHis film ''[[Alila]]'' (2003) participated in [[Venice Film Festival]] 2003, starring [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Hana Laszlo]],<ref>[[:fr:Hana Laszlo]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}} [[Ronit Elkabetz]], Liron Levo, Tomer Russo, Lupo Berkowitch, Amos Lavi, [[Yosef Carmon]].\n<ref>\n[http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=74&lang=1 Alila on Amos Gitai site]\n</ref>\n\nIn 2004 he directed ''[[Promised Land (2004 film)|Promised Land]]'', the first film of the \"Frontier Trilogy\". It was followed by ''[[Free Zone (film)|Free Zone]]'' (2005) and ''[[Disengagement (film)|Disengagement]]'' (2007). ''Promised Land'' was in competition at the [[61st Venice International Film Festival]], starring [[Rosamund Pike]], [[Diana Bespechni]], [[Hanna Schygulla]], and [[Anne Parillaud]].\n<ref>\nFelperin, Leslie (13 September 2004). \n[https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/promised-land-4-1200531097/ Promised Land review]. [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]].\n</ref>\n''Free Zone'' was screened in competition at the [[2005 Cannes Film Festival]], where its star [[Hannah Laslo]] received the prize for the best female actress. starring also [[Natalie Portman]] and [[Hiam Abbass]].<ref>Holden,\n Stephen (APRIL 7, 2006).\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/07/movies/an-allegorical-plea-for-harmony-in-the-middle-east-in-free-zone.html An Allegorical Plea for Harmony in the Middle East in 'Free Zone']. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[File:Gitai Fortman Laslo.tif|thumb|Amos Gita\u00ef with [[Hanna Laslo]] and [[Natalie Portman]], shooting of film'' [[Free Zone (film)|Free Zone]]'', 2005]]\n\n''Ana Arabia'' (2013) was entered into the main competition at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]].\n<ref>\n(25 July 2013).\n[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jul/25/venice-film-festival-2013-line-up Venice film festival 2013: the full line-up]. ''[[The Guardian]]''\n</ref>\nStarring [[Yuval Scharf]], [[Yussuf Abu-Warda]], [[Sarah Adler]], [[Assi Levy]], [[Uri Gavriel]], and [[Norman Issa]].\n<ref>\nFrodon, Jean-Michel (5 August 2014).\n[http://www.slate.fr/story/90631/ana-arabia \u00abAna Arabia\u00bb: un labyrinthe pour la paix]. ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''.\n</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, his film ''[[Rabin, the Last Day]]'' had its world premiere in the competition at the [[72nd Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>http://www.haaretz.com/life/movies-television/.premium-1.642991</ref> and at the Toronto International Fim Festival (Masters), starring Yitzhak Hiskiya, Michael Warshaviak, [[Tomer Sisley]], Tomer Russo, Uri Gottlieb, Dalia Shimko, Gdalya Besser, Liron Levo and [[Yael Abecassis]].\n<ref>{{cite web |last=Young |first=Deborah |date=9 July 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/rabin-last-day-venice-review-820825 |title=Rabin, The Last Day: Venice Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\nOn the evening of Saturday, 4 November 1995, Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin was shot down at the end of a huge political rally in the center of Tel-Aviv. His killer apprehended at the scene turned out to be a 25-year-old Jewish observant. Investigation into this brutal murder reveals a dark and frightening world that made this tragic deed possible. A subculture of hate fueled by hysterical rhetoric, paranoia and political intrigue. The extremist rabbis who condemned Rabin by invoking an obscure Talmudic ruling. The prominent right wing politicians who joined in a campaign of incitement against Rabin. The militant Israeli settlers for whom peace meant betrayal. \nAnd the security agents who saw what was coming and failed to prevent it. The film sheds light on an ever-growing crisis of hate in Israeli society today. \nGitai combines staged re-enactments with actual news footage of the shooting and its aftermath to create a thought-provoking political thriller.<ref>https://charlierose.com/videos/23077.htm{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n\"A few years ago we decided to make this project on the assassination of Rabin as a kind of a gesture about memory and even in the hope that sometimes when you resurrect memory, it can create movements. But we have to be modest about it: art is not the most efficient way to change reality. Politics or machine guns have a much more direct effect. But sometimes art has some delayed effect, because it conserves memory when big powers want to erase it, because they call for obedience, they don't want to be disturbed, they don't want dissent. But if artists are loyal to their inner truth, they produce works which voyage in time, which don't always have immediate effects, sometimes they have delayed effects. I hope that this is something that we do with this multi-format presentation, with a film installation, a performance, and research materials about and around the assassination of Yitzhak Rabin\" (Amos Gitai).\n\nIn 2017, Amos Gitai returns to the occupied territories for the first time since his 1982 documentary \"Field Diary\". \"WEST OF THE JORDAN RIVER\" describes the efforts of Israelis and Palestinians citizens, who try to overcome the consequences of the occupation. Gitai's documentary shows the human ties woven by the military, human rights activists, journalists, mourning mothers and even Jewish settlers. Faced with the failure of politics to solve the occupation, these men and women rise and act in the name of their civic consciousness. This human energy is a proposal for long overdue change. The film was premiered in Cannes International Film Festival 2017 \u2013 Directors' Fortnight.\n\n2018 is a year of intense activity for Amos Gitai, who presents at [[the Venice Film Festival]] \"A TRAMWAY IN JERUSALEM\", a light-hearted and dramatic fare on a tramway that connects several of Jerusalem's neighborhoods from East to West, bringing together a mosaic of people from different religious and ethnic backgrounds. \"The film describes an ironic, almost utopian situation in which most of the conflicts are contained and this beautiful city of Jerusalem charged with thousands of years of history facilitates people\u2019s way of living side by side.\" (Amos Gitai) \nCast: [[Mathieu Amalric]], [[Pippo Delbono]], [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Hanna Laszlo]], among 36 Israeli, Palestinian and European actors and actresses.\n\nThe film is preceded by Amos Gitai's \"[[A LETTER TO A FRIEND IN GAZA]]\" (2018, 34 mins, in Hebrew & Arabic). The film responds to the current crisis between Israel and Gaza. 2 Palestinians and 2 Israelis read texts inspired by [[Mahmoud Darwish]], [[Yizhar Smilansky]], [[Emile Habibi]] and [[Amira Hass]], as an homage to a famous letter written by [[Albert Camus]] in 1943, which gives its title to the film.\n\n===Novel adaptations===\nGitai created several novel adaptations. ''One day you'll understand'' (\"Plus tard tu comprendras\", 2008) is based on an autobiographical book by [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Cl\u00e9ment]], president of the Arte television channel and one of the leading figures of French culture, and tells the story of a French writer tracing the story of his Jewish mother ([[Jeanne Moreau]]) and her family during World War II.<ref>[[:fr:J\u00e9r\u00f4me Cl\u00e9ment]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n<ref>A. O. Scott. (30 October 2008).\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/31/movies/31unde.html In Search of Family History Despite the Threat of Pain]. [[The New York Times]]\n</ref>\n''[[Roses \u00e0 cr\u00e9dit]]'' (2010) is an adaptation of the novel by [[Elsa Triolet]] and takes a look at the materialist, post-war world of the French lower middle-class.<ref>http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2010/rosescredit#filmnote  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010073126/http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2010/rosescredit#filmnote |date=10 October 2011 }}</ref>  The film was shot entirely in France. ''[[Tsili]]'' (2014) is inspired by the novel by [[Aharon Appelfeld]], and tells the story of the wandering of its heroine submerged in the nightmare of the war. Tsili, a young Jewish woman, gathers all the forces of intuition and vitality to survive in this desperate universe. \nstarring [[Sarah Adler]], Meshi Olinski, and [[Lea Koenig]].\n<ref>https://www.huffingtonpost.com/e-nina-rothe/best-of-venice-with-tsili_b_5815176.html</ref>\n\"I was inspired by what Aharon Appelfeld told Philip Roth :The reality of the Holocaust surpassed any imagination. If I remained true to the facts, no one would believe me. But the moment I chose a girl, a little older than I was at that time, I removed ''the story of my life'' from the mighty grip of memory and gave it over to the creative laboratory. There memory is not the only proprietor. There one needs a causal explanation, a thread to tie things together. The exceptional is permissible only if it is part of an overall structure and contributes to its understanding. \nWhen I wrote ''Tsili'' I was interested in the possibilities of naiveness in art. Can there be a naive modern art? It seemed to me that without the naivete still found among children and old people and, to some extent, in ourselves, the work of art would be flawed. I tried to correct that flaw.\" (Amos Gitai)\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Amos Gitai and Arthur Miller\".jpg|thumb|Amos Gitai and Arthur Miller]] -->\n\n===Exhibitions, publications and performances===\nGitai\u2019s work include film installations, stage work and books publications. Various publications and exhibitions took place, devoted to his parents Munio and Efratia: Traces at the Palais de Tokyo (Paris), the [[Bauhaus]] (Dessau, Germany), the art museum of the Ein Harod kibbutz (Israel), and Kib- butz Kfar Masaryk Dining Hall at the MoMA (New York, 2013). Retrospective and installation at the Museo nazionale del cinema in Turin.\nIn 2010 Gitai presents at The Od\u00e9on-Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de l\u2019Europe \"The War of the Sons of Light against the Sons of Darkness\", a work staged in the Boulbon quarry, at the Avignon Festival (July 2009). He publishes as well the letters of his mother Efratia (Efratia Gitai: Correspondence 1929\u20131994, Gallimard), which are read by Jeanne Moreau at the Od\u00e9on-Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de l\u2019Europe and on France Culture. In 2011 Gitai inaugurated the Munio Gitai Weinraub Architecture Museum in his father's old offices in Haifa.<ref>http://ropac.net/artist/amos-gitai</ref><ref>http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xhp9ae_traces-d-amos-gitai-au-palais-de-tokyo_creation</ref>\n\nAfter the premier of his film 'Rabin, the Last Day', Gitai continues his investigation into the assassination of the Israeli Prime Minister with an installation \u00ab Chronicle of an assassination foretold \u00bb presented at the MAXXI Museum (Rome),<ref>http://www.fondazionemaxxi.it/en/events/cronaca-di-un-assassinio-annunciato.html{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Bozar Museum (Brussels)<ref>http://www.bozar.be/fr/activities/112519-amos-gitai.html</ref> and the Fondation Lambert en Avignon.<ref>http://www.collectionlambert.fr/7/expositions/en-cours.html</ref> Ceramics, photographs, and video installations propose a new reading of the events that led to the assassination of the Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin on 4 November 1995, in Tel Aviv.<ref>https://www.ft.com/content/b63bb70e-484f-11e6-8d68-72e9211e86ab)</ref>\n\nThis installation also echoes a theatrical performance given in July 2016 in the Cour d'honneur of the Palais des papes at the Festival d'Avignon. In Yitzhak Rabin : chronique d\u2019un assassinat, Gitai uses the memories of Leah Rabin, the Prime Minister's widow, as a springboard. Four voices (two actresses, Hiam Abbass and Sarah Adler, and two musicians, Edna Stern (piano) and [[Sonia Wieder-Atherton]] (cello) create a recitative, \u201chalfway between lament and lullaby,\u201d to travel back through History and explore the incredible violence with which the nationalist forces fought the peace project, tearing Israel apart. Four voices caught \u201clike in an echo chamber,\u201d between image-documents and excerpts from classic and contemporary literature.\n\nIn July 2016, a 540-page book on Amos Gitai was published by Galerie Enrico Navarra and S\u00e9bastien Moreu. The book includes more than 250 reproductions from movies and research, but also family archives and creations by Amos Gitai and 7 conversations between Gitai and : [[Hans-Ulrich Obrist]], [[Guy Amsellem]], [[Arthur Miller]], [[Hou Hanru]], [[Annette Michelson]], [[Richard Ingersoll]], [[Elisabeth Lebovici]] & [[Stephan Levine]]), two poems (Mount Carmel and Lullaby to My Father) and a poetic essay on the Golem.\n<ref>[[\u00c9lisabeth Lebovici]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\nOn 8 October 2018, the [[Philharmonie de Paris]] presents \"[[Yitzhak Rabin Chronicle of an Assassination]]\" created in Avignon in 2016, with [[Barbara Hendricks]], [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Sarah Adler]], [[Gavriel Lipkind]] (cello), [[Edna Stern]] (piano).\n\n==Personal life==\nGitai was born in Haifa and divides his time today between Paris and Haifa.\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Golem l'esprit de l'exil - Shemesh and Schygulla - 1992.jpg|thumbnail|right|250px|[[Ophrah Shemesh]] and [[Hanna Schygulla]] in ''[[Golem, the Spirit of the Exile]]'', 1991]]\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''My Mother at the Seashore'' (1973)\n* ''Bayit'' (1980)\n* ''Yoman Sadeh'' (1982)\n* ''Bangkok-Bahrein'' (1983) \n* ''Ananas'' (1984)\n* ''[[Esther (1986 film)|Esther]]'' (1986)\n* ''Brand New Day''\n* ''[[Berlin-Jerusalem]]'' (1989)\n* ''{{ill|Birth of a Golem|fr|Naissance d'un Golem}}'' (1991)\n* ''[[Golem, the Spirit of the Exile]]'' (1992)\n* ''{{ill|Zihron Devarim|fr|Devarim (film)}}'' (1995)\n* ''Zirat Ha'Rezach'' (1996)\n* ''[[Metamorphosis of a Melody]]'' (1996)\n* ''War and Peace in Vesoul'' (1997)\n* ''{{ill|A House in Jerusalem|it}}'' (1998)\n* ''Orange'' (1998)\n* ''Zion, Auto-Emancipation'' (1998)\n* ''{{ill|Yom Yom|fr}}'' (1998)\n* ''[[Kadosh]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Kippur]]'' (2000)\n* ''{{ill|Eden (2001 film)|lt=Eden|fr|Eden (film, 2001)}}'' (2001)\n* ''[[Kedma (film)|Kedma]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[11'09\"01 September 11]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Alila]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Promised Land (2004 film)|Promised Land]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Free Zone (film)|Free Zone]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Disengagement (film)|Disengagement]]'' (2007)\n* ''{{ill|One day you'll understand|fr|Plus tard tu comprendras}}'' (2008)\n* ''{{ill|Carmel (film 2009)|it|lt=Carmel}}'' (2009)\n* ''The War of the Sons of Light Against the Sons of Darkness'' (2009)\n* ''{{lang|fr|[[Roses \u00e0 cr\u00e9dit]]}}'' (2010)\n* ''[[Lullaby to My Father]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Ana Arabia]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Words With Gods]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Tsili]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Rabin, the Last Day]]'' (2015)\n* ''West of the Jordan River'' (2017)\n* ''{{ill|A Tramway in Jerusalem|fr|Un tramway \u00e0 J\u00e9rusalem}}'' (2018)\n* ''Letter to A Friend in Gaza'' (2018)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Exhibitions, performances==\n* The Law Of The Pursuer. An Essay Exhibition, [http://savvy-contemporary.com SAVVY Contemporary] Berlin, Germany, February - March 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://savvy-contemporary.com/index.php/exhibitions/the-law-of-the-pursuer/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209052540/http://savvy-contemporary.com/index.php/exhibitions/the-law-of-the-pursuer |archive-date=9 February 2017 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Chronique d'un assassinat, theater performance, 72nd festival d'Avignon, France, July 2016<ref>http://www.festival-avignon.com/fr/.html</ref>\n* Chronique d'un assassinat annonc\u00e9 - Exhibition in Fondation Lambert in Avignon, France, 3 July \u2013 6 November 2016<ref>/http://www.collectionlambert.fr/evenement/217/l-ete-a-la-collection-lambert.html</ref>\n* Exhibition at the galerie Thaddeus Ropac, Salzburg, Austria, 2015<ref>http://ropac.net/selected_works/amos-gitai</ref>\n* Ways/Strade, Palazzo Reale, Milan, 2014-2015\n* Amos Gitai biografias, Mus\u00e9e Reina Sofia, 2014 (commissaires : Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Chevrier, Elia Pijollet).\n* Amos Gitai Architecte de la m\u00e9moire, Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que fran\u00e7aise (Paris), Mus\u00e9e de l\u2019\u00c9lys\u00e9e (Lausanne), Galerie des Beaux Arts (Bruxelles), 2014 (commissaire : Matthieu Orl\u00e9an)\n* Before and After, galerie Thaddeus Ropac, Paris Pantin, 2014 et Villa Kast, Salzbourg, 2015\n* Disaster / The End of Days (exposition collective), galerie Thaddeus Ropac, Paris, 2013\n* Architecture de la m\u00e9moire, installation, \u00c9glise des Fr\u00e8res pr\u00eacheurs, rencontres photographiques d\u2019Arles, 2012<ref>http://www.rencontres-arles.com/C.aspx?VP3=CMS3&VF=ARL_791.html</ref>\n* ''Correspondence, Efrati Gitai \u2013 Letters'', [[Ein Harod#Museums|Museum of Art, Ein Harod]],  Israel, 2011\n* ''Traces - Munio Gitai \u2013 Weinraub'', Museum of Art, Ein Harod,  Israel, 2011\n* ''Traces'', an installation at the [[Palais de Tokyo]], Paris, 2011<ref>{{cite web|last=Anderman |first=Nirit |url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/amos-gitai-exhibit-on-father-opens-in-paris-1.341700 |title=Amos Gitai exhibit on father opens in Paris - Haaretz Daily Newspaper &#124; Israel News |publisher=Haaretz.com |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105065824/http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/amos-gitai-exhibit-on-father-opens-in-paris-1.341700|archivedate=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Lullaby for my father'', a video presentation in Kibbutz Kfar Masaryk, Israel, 2010\n* ''The War of the Sons of Light Against the Sons of Darkness'', (with ''[[Jeanne Moreau]]''), [[Festival d'Avignon]], France, 2009\n* ''Traces'' - Evento, [[Bordeaux]], 2009\n* ''Munio Weinraub / Amos Gitai - Architecture und Film in Israel'', Pinakothek der Moderne, ArchitekturMuseum, Munich, 2008-2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architekturmuseum.de/en/ausstellungen/detail.php?which=164 |title=Architekturmuseum der TU M\u00fcnchen [Exhibitions&#93; |publisher=Architekturmuseum.de |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313085852/http://www.architekturmuseum.de/en/ausstellungen/detail.php?which=164|archivedate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n* Munio Weinraub / Amos Gitai - Architecture and Film in Israel, Tel Aviv Museum, [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]] 2008-2009\n* ''Amos Gitai: Non-Fiction'', [[MoMA]] (Museum of Modern Art) New York, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/638 |title=MoMA &#124; MoMA Presents: Amos Gitai's News from Home/News from House |publisher=Google.co.il |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303193558/https://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/638|archivedate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Exhibition in memory of his father Munia Gitai \u2013 Weinraub'' - Amos Gitai, Olivier Cinqualbre and Lionel Richard, [[Centre Pompidou]], Paris 2006\n* ''Public Housing'' - long video presentation screens, Ein Harod Museum, Herzliya Museum, Saitama Museum of Modern Art, [[Saitama, Saitama|Saitama]], Japan, 2000\n* ''Open Shen Zen'' - Performance, [[Helena Rubinstein#Divorce and remarriage|Helena Rubinstein Pavilion]], Tel - Aviv 1998\n* ''Exhibition in memory to his father - Munio Gitai \u2013 Weinraub'', [[Israel Museum|Jerusalem Museum]], Israel, 1994\n\n==Books==\n* ''Efratia Gitai \u2013 letters'', Yediot books, Israel, 2011\n* ''Efratia Gitai, {{lang|fr|Correspondence}} (1929\u20131994)''', Gallimard, Paris, 2010\n* ''Gen\u00e8ses'', ''Jean-Michel Frodon, Amos Gitai, Marie-Jos\u00e9 Sanselme'', Gallimard, Paris, 2009\n* ''Monte Carmelo'', Amos Gitai, Bompiani, Milano, 2004\n* ''[[Parcours]]'', Amos Gitai, Centre Pompidou, Paris, 2003\n* ''Mont Carmel'', Amos Gitai, Gallimard, 2003\n* ''Munio Gitai Weinraub, Bauhaus architect in Israel'', Richard Ingersoll, Electa, Milano, 1994\n* ''[[The War of the Sons of Light Against the Sons of Darkness]]'', Amos Gitai,  Mazzotta, Milano, 1993\n\n==Books on Amos Gitai's work==\n* ''Amos Gitai'', Galerie Enrico Navarra, \u00e9ditions S\u00e9bastien Moreu, Paris, 2016\n* ''Cinema di Amos Gitai: Frontiere e territori (Il)'', Serge Toubiana, Bruno Mondadori, Torino, 2006\n* ''Amos Gitai: News from Home'', Walther K\u00f6nig, K\u00f6ln, 2006\n* ''The Cinema of Amos Gitai'',''Serge Toubiana'', Baptiste Pi\u00e9gay, Lincoln Center / Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, Paris, 2005\n* ''Amos Gitai'', ''Serge Toubiana'', Mostra internacional de cinema / Cosac Naify, S\u00e3o Paulo, 2004\n* ''Exilios y territories, el cine de Amos Gitai'', Serge Toubiana, Baptiste Pi\u00e9gay, Semana Internacional de Cine, Valladolid, 2004\n* ''Exils et territoires: le cin\u00e9ma d'Amos Gitai'', Serge Toubiana, Baptiste Pi\u00e9gay, Arte Editions / Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, Paris, 2003\n* ''Amos Gitai, Cinema, Politics, Aesthetics'', Irma Klein, KM, Tel Aviv, 2003\n* ''Amos Gitai, Cinema forza di pace'', Edited by Daniela Turco, Le Mani, Genova, 2002\n* ''The Films of Amos Gitai'', a Montage, Edited by Paul Willemen, BFI Publishing, London, 1993\n* ''Amos Gitai'', Edited by Alberto Farassino, Mostra Internazionale Riminicinema, Rimini, 1989\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nAmos Gitai: Exile and Atonement, ''Ray Privett'', Cinema Purgatorio, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Amos Gitai}}\n* [http://www.amosgitai.com/ Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|321159}}\n* [http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/188299/Amos_Gitai Amos Gitai], Hollywood.com\n{{Amos Gitai}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gitai, Amos}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Haifa]]\n[[Category:Israeli filmmakers]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:Israeli screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Israeli architects]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli film directors]]\n[[Category:Roberto Rossellini Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of the Yom Kippur War]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley College of Environmental Design alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli film director and screenwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Amos portrait 1.jpg\n| name         = Amos Gitai\n| caption      = Gitai in 2008\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1950|10|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Haifa]], Israel\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Filmmaker\n*author}}\n| alma_mater   = {{Unbulleted list|[[Technion]]|[[University of California, Berkeley]]}}\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Rivka Gitai|1980}}\n| parents      = [[Munio Weinraub]]\n| children     =\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| website      = {{URL|amosgitai.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Amos Gitai''' ({{lang-he|\u05e2\u05de\u05d5\u05e1 \u05d2\u05d9\u05ea\u05d0\u05d9}}; born 11 October 1950) is an [[Israelis|Israeli]] filmmaker, who was trained as an architect.\n\nGitai's work was presented in several major retrospectives in [[Pompidou Center]] Paris, the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA) New York, [[Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts|Lincoln Center]] New York, and the [[British Film Institute]] London. To date Amos Gitai has created over 90 works of art throughout 38 years. Between 1999 and 2017 ten of his films were entered in the [[Cannes Film Festival]] for the [[Palme d'Or]] as well as The [[Venice Film Festival|Venice International Film Festival]] for the [[Golden Lion]] award.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}} He has worked with [[Juliette Binoche]], [[Jeanne Moreau]], [[Natalie Portman]], [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Samuel Fuller]], [[Hanna Schygulla]], [[Annie Lennox]], [[Barbara Hendricks]], [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]], [[Valeria Bruni Tedeschi]], [[Henri Alekan]], [[Renato Berta]], [[Nurith Aviv]], [[\u00c9ric Gautier]] and more. Since 2000 he has been collaborating with the French screenwriter Marie-Jos\u00e9 Sanselme. He received several prestigious prizes, in particular the Leopard of Honor at the Locarno International Film Festival (2008), the Roberto Rossellini prize (2005), the Robert Bresson prize (2013), the Paradjanov prize (2014), and [[L\u00e9gion d'Honneur]] (2017).<ref>\n(29 October 2017).[http://www.parismatch.com/Culture/Cinema/Le-cineaste-Amos-Gitai-a-recu-la-Legion-d-Honneur-1381430 Le cin\u00e9aste Amos Gitai a re\u00e7u la L\u00e9gion d'Honneur]. [[Paris Match]].</ref> In 2018, Amos Gitai has been elected professor at the chair of artistic creation at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]], with a series of 12 lessons on cinema (16 October \u2013 18 December 2018)\n\n==Early life==\nGitai was born to [[Munio Weinraub]] (Gitai), an architect formed at the [[Interbellum|pre-war]] German [[Bauhaus]] art school, and to [[Efratia Margalit]], an intellectual, storyteller and a teacher.<ref name=\"Cannes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmfestivals.com/cannes99/html/seloff4.htm |title=Film Festival : Cannes 99 |publisher=Filmfestivals.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629183721/http://www.filmfestivals.com/cannes99/html/seloff4.htm |archivedate=29 June 2011 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |url= http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=5&lang=1 |title= Conversation Amos Gitai / Peter Cowie|work=Amos Gitai official homepage |accessdate=26 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215071253/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=5&lang=1|archivedate=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"IMDb\">{{IMDb name|0321159}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=60&lang=1 |title=Munio Weinraub Gitai Architect (1909-1970) &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091015183905/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=60&lang=1|archivedate=15 October 2009}}</ref> He holds a degree in Architecture from the [[Technion]] in Haifa and a PhD in Architecture from the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. \n\nIn 1973, during the [[Yom Kippur War]], Gitai had to interrupt his architecture studies as he was called up to reserve service as part of a helicopter rescue crew. While serving, he shot 8mm footage of the fighting, and said this served as his entry into the world of film making.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=2&lang=1 |title=Biography &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707135035/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/page.asp?docid=2&lang=1| archivedate= 7 July 2011 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Film career==\n\n===Trilogies===\n[[File:Amos Gitai Jeanne Moreau.jpg|thumb|Amos Gitai and [[Jeanne Moreau]] at the ''One day you'll understand'' shooting, (2008)]]\nGitai began his career directing mostly documentaries. In 1980 he directed his first full-length Israeli film, Home (1980), the first part of the House Trilogy: ''Home'' (1980) ''A House in Jerusalem'' (1998), ''News from Home / News from House'' (2005). The film follows a house in West Jerusalem, abandoned during the 1948 war by its Palestinian owner. It was rejected and was censored by Israeli television; however, it was screened at the Berlin and the Rotterdam International Film Festivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=36&lang=0 |title=House / La Maison &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328095650/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=36&lang=0|archivedate=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHouse was the first trilogy of many others; a concept Gitai consistently worked with during his career, offering a complex and layered view on the Geo-political Israeli reality.\n\n\"Gita\u00ef wants this house to be both a symbol and something very concrete; he wants it to become a character in a film. He achieves one of the most beautiful things a camera can register 'live', as it were; people who look at the same thing but see different things - and who are moved by that vision. In this crumbling shell of a house, real hallucinations begin to take shape. The film's central idea is simple and the film has simply the force of that idea, no more, no less.\" (Serge Daney, Lib\u00e9ration, 1 March 1982)\n\nWadi (''Wadi'' 1981, ''Wadi Ten Years After'' 1991, ''Wadi Grand Canyon'' 2001), similar to House is dealing with a specific location and examines the complex relationships between the residents of the former stone quarry: Eastern European immigrants, survivors of the camps and Arabs who have also been expelled from their homes. Gitai turns the valley into a symbol of a possible coexistence.<ref>http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=39&lang=1</ref>\n \nIn 1982 he directed \"Field Diary\" (1982). A film-diary shot in the occupied territories before and during the invasion of Lebanon and, creating a controversy and leading to Gitai leaving Israel for France (1983-1993).<ref>{{cite web|author=Ramesh Jaura |url=http://www.indepthnews.net/news/news.php?key1=2011-05-10%2018:28:47&key2=1 |title=IDN-InDepthNews &#124; Analysis That Matters |publisher=Indepthnews.net |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=15 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331005249/http://www.indepthnews.net/news/news.php?key1=2011-05-10%2018%3A28%3A47&key2=1 |archivedate=31 March 2012 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\"'Field Diary\u201d offers a civilian image of war, [\u2026] setting it apart from the rest of audio-visual production by its content as much as by its mode of operation, by the solution it offers to a problem that pertains to the ethics of the filmmaker as much as to the aesthetics of cinema\" (Yann Lardeau, \"Une \u00e9thique du travelling\", Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, n\u00b0344, February 1983).\n\nGitai created as well fiction trilogies. The \"Exile Trilogy\" composed of ''[[Esther (1986 film)|Esther]]'', 1985 that tells the Old Testament story of Esther, who does not know she is Jewish when she is chosen by King Ashasuerus as his wife and was presented at the International Critics\u2019 Week of the [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n<ref>\nStephen Holden (19 May 1989).\n[https://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/19/movies/reviews-film-the-purim-story-with-modern-overtones.html Reviews/Film; The Purim Story, With Modern Overtones]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.\n</ref>\n''Berlin-J\u00e9rusalem'', 1989 was based on the biographies of the German expressionist poet, [[Else Lasker-Sch\u00fcler]], and the Russian Zionist, [[Mania Shohat]], and their respective itineraries towards the mythical Jerusalem of the 1930s.<ref>Fred Camper, \"Face to Face With History\", ''Chicago Reader'', 1989</ref><ref>Mansel Stimpson, \"Amos Gitai Branches Out\", ''What's on in London'', 6 March 1991</ref> The film competed in the [[46th Venice International Film Festival]] and won first prize at the [[Istanbul Festival]]. leading actresses:\n[[Lisa Kreuzer]], [[Rivka Neumann]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=46&lang=1 |title=Berlin-Jerusalem &#124; The Films of Amos Gitai |publisher=Amosgitai.com |date= |accessdate=29 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328095654/http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=46&lang=1|archivedate=28 March 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Golem, the Spirit of the Exile]]'', 1991 which explores the contemporary meanings of the Book of Ruth in the Bible.<ref>http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=48&lang=1</ref>\n\n\"The director holds the story at an analytical distance. Events are re-enacted in a sequence of ritual tableaux shot in the ruins of Wadi Salib, the old Arab neighbourhood of Haifa that the Palestinians abandoned after the 1948 war. The sense of ancient unsettled scores that have simmered for centuries is almost palpable in this beautiful but ravaged territory. In the most striking shots, the actors seem to blend into the architecture like the figures in Persian miniatures. These shots are pointedly contrasted with others photographed in the same vicinity, which make it look like a squalid contemporary junkyard. The juxtapositions suggest how overwhelmingly the region's history continues to haunt Israel's present.\" (Stephen Holden, ''The New York Times'', 19 May 1989)\n\n[[File:Gitai88.jpg|thumb|250px|Amos Gitai and [[Henri Alekan]], shooting Esther, 1986.]]\n\nThe \"City Trilogy\" (''[[Devarim (film)|Devarim]]'', 1995 ; ''[[Yom Yom]]'', 1998 ; ''[[Kadosh]]'', 1999), was created after Gitai's return to Israel in 1993, after [[Yitzhak Rabin]]\u2019s victory in the elections and the [[Oslo Accords]]. Each film is dedicated to a different city in Israel: \"Devarim\" takes place in Tel Aviv, and is after the novel by Yaakov Shabtai, Past Continuous. The film depicts the spiritual disarray of three men in their thirties and forties, in the agitation and turmoil of Tel Aviv, the city created by Jewish pioneers in 1909. None of them has the life he had imagined. \"Yom Yom\" draws upon Haifa's tradition of peaceful coexistence between Arab and Jewish neighbours to tell a dark comic tale of characters driven by divided loyalties and neurotic inhibitions. Leslie Camhi wrote \"Gita\u00ef\u2019s genius is to show the conflict infiltrating every encounter, from the marketplace to the bedroom and beyond; the vivid portraits of Israeli social types, whether arrogant reservists or hapless nebbishes, stand in sharp contrast to images promoted in the media.\" (Leslie Camhi, Village Voice, 20 February 2001). \n''[[Kadosh]]'' is set in [[Mea Shearim]], the ultra-orthodox neighbourhood of Jerusalem and tells the story of Me\u00efr and Rivka, that have been married for ten years but have to divorce because they have no children. Actors: [[Yael Abecassis]], Samuel Calderon, [[Lea Koenig]], [[Yussuf Abu-Warda]], Uri Klauzner, [[Rivka Michaeli]], Yoram Hattab.\n<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C06E6D81531F935A25751C0A9669C8B63</ref>\nThe review in ''The Wall Street Journal'':\n''Kadosh'' - \"the title means \"sacred\" - addresses universal themes. Among them are the demands of ultra-orthodox religion, which confines as it sustains, and the suffering of men and women whose religion comes before love, but whose culture lacks a vocabulary for expressing personal pain. Yet Kadosh is also foreign in the extreme, an austere and shocking portrait of daily life in Mea Shearim, the Hasidic Jewish quarter of Jerusalem. ( ... ) Kadosh is a horror story, or rather two horror stories intertwined, about women tyrannised by men in the name of religious belief.\"\n(The Wall Street Journal, 17 March 2000)\n\"Kadosh\" was entered into the [[1999 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>[http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/kadosh Kadosh in 1999 Cannes Film Festival]</ref>\n\nAnother fiction trilogy deals with important historical events in Israel: ''[[Kippur]]'', 2000; ''[[Eden (2001 film)|Eden]]'', 2001; ''[[Kedma (film)|Kedma]]'', 2002.\n''Kippur''  (2000) was Israel's first large-scale cinematic depiction of the considerably difficult and traumatic [[Yom Kippur War]] of 1973. Critics praised its absence of sensationalism and its unsentimental depiction of war.<ref>{{cite web|author= TV Guide Network New |url=http://movies.tvguide.com/kippur/review/134913 |title=Kippur Review |publisher=Movies.tvguide.com |date= |accessdate=2 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528021917/http://movies.tvguide.com/kippur/review/134913|archivedate=28 May 2012}}</ref>\nCharles Tesson wrote in ''Les Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma'': \"Throughout the film, the viewer remains locked in this absurd question: are we in the war or is that happening somewhere else, off-screen, or was it happening just before the camera got there? We never know for certain and then we realise that this uncertainty is in fact the most profound truth of war, as cinema has hardly ever shown it, with a force and an intensity that takes your breath away. [\u2026] The principle for filming warfare in Kippur is simple, limpid. Favouring real time spaces, [\u2026] making the camera an extra person walking with the soldiers, running behind the others to get on the helicopter before it takes off. The viewer is inside the war while remaining outside the group, accompanying them. Never does the film encourage in the viewer that fantasy of being one of them.\" (Charles Tesson, Les Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma, n\u00b0549, September 2000).\n''Kippur'' was entered into the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]] starring Liron Levo, Tomer Russo, Uri Klauzner, Yoram Hattab and [[Juliano Mer-Khamis]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/5157/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Kippur |accessdate=2009-10-10|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> \n''Eden'' competed in the Venice Biennale 2001.<ref>\n[http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=69&lang=1 Eden on Amos Gitai site] \n</ref> \n''Kedma'' was entered into the [[2002 Cannes Film Festival]]. Its leading actors are Andrei Kashkar and Helena Yaralova. \n<ref>\n[http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/kedma \"Festival de Cannes: Kedma\"]. festival-cannes.com.\n</ref>\n\nHis film ''[[Alila]]'' (2003) participated in [[Venice Film Festival]] 2003, starring [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Hana Laszlo]],<ref>[[:fr:Hana Laszlo]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}} [[Ronit Elkabetz]], Liron Levo, Tomer Russo, Lupo Berkowitch, Amos Lavi, [[Yosef Carmon]].\n<ref>\n[http://www.amosgitai.com/html/film.asp?docid=74&lang=1 Alila on Amos Gitai site]\n</ref>\n\nIn 2004 he directed ''[[Promised Land (2004 film)|Promised Land]]'', the first film of the \"Frontier Trilogy\". It was followed by ''[[Free Zone (film)|Free Zone]]'' (2005) and ''[[Disengagement (film)|Disengagement]]'' (2007). ''Promised Land'' was in competition at the [[61st Venice International Film Festival]], starring [[Rosamund Pike]], [[Diana Bespechni]], [[Hanna Schygulla]], and [[Anne Parillaud]].\n<ref>\nFelperin, Leslie (13 September 2004). \n[https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/promised-land-4-1200531097/ Promised Land review]. [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]].\n</ref>\n''Free Zone'' was screened in competition at the [[2005 Cannes Film Festival]], where its star [[Hannah Laslo]] received the prize for the best female actress. starring also [[Natalie Portman]] and [[Hiam Abbass]].<ref>Holden,\n Stephen (APRIL 7, 2006).\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/07/movies/an-allegorical-plea-for-harmony-in-the-middle-east-in-free-zone.html An Allegorical Plea for Harmony in the Middle East in 'Free Zone']. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[File:Gitai Fortman Laslo.tif|thumb|Amos Gita\u00ef with [[Hanna Laslo]] and [[Natalie Portman]], shooting of film'' [[Free Zone (film)|Free Zone]]'', 2005]]\n\n''Ana Arabia'' (2013) was entered into the main competition at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]].\n<ref>\n(25 July 2013).\n[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jul/25/venice-film-festival-2013-line-up Venice film festival 2013: the full line-up]. ''[[The Guardian]]''\n</ref>\nStarring [[Yuval Scharf]], [[Yussuf Abu-Warda]], [[Sarah Adler]], [[Assi Levy]], [[Uri Gavriel]], and [[Norman Issa]].\n<ref>\nFrodon, Jean-Michel (5 August 2014).\n[http://www.slate.fr/story/90631/ana-arabia \u00abAna Arabia\u00bb: un labyrinthe pour la paix]. ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''.\n</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, his film ''[[Rabin, the Last Day]]'' had its world premiere in the competition at the [[72nd Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>http://www.haaretz.com/life/movies-television/.premium-1.642991</ref> and at the Toronto International Fim Festival (Masters), starring Yitzhak Hiskiya, Michael Warshaviak, [[Tomer Sisley]], Tomer Russo, Uri Gottlieb, Dalia Shimko, Gdalya Besser, Liron Levo and [[Yael Abecassis]].\n<ref>{{cite web |last=Young |first=Deborah |date=9 July 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/rabin-last-day-venice-review-820825 |title=Rabin, The Last Day: Venice Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\nOn the evening of Saturday, 4 November 1995, Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin was shot down at the end of a huge political rally in the center of Tel-Aviv. His killer apprehended at the scene turned out to be a 25-year-old Jewish observant. Investigation into this brutal murder reveals a dark and frightening world that made this tragic deed possible. A subculture of hate fueled by hysterical rhetoric, paranoia and political intrigue. The extremist rabbis who condemned Rabin by invoking an obscure Talmudic ruling. The prominent right wing politicians who joined in a campaign of incitement against Rabin. The militant Israeli settlers for whom peace meant betrayal. \nAnd the security agents who saw what was coming and failed to prevent it. The film sheds light on an ever-growing crisis of hate in Israeli society today. \nGitai combines staged re-enactments with actual news footage of the shooting and its aftermath to create a thought-provoking political thriller.<ref>https://charlierose.com/videos/23077.htm{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n\"A few years ago we decided to make this project on the assassination of Rabin as a kind of a gesture about memory and even in the hope that sometimes when you resurrect memory, it can create movements. But we have to be modest about it: art is not the most efficient way to change reality. Politics or machine guns have a much more direct effect. But sometimes art has some delayed effect, because it conserves memory when big powers want to erase it, because they call for obedience, they don't want to be disturbed, they don't want dissent. But if artists are loyal to their inner truth, they produce works which voyage in time, which don't always have immediate effects, sometimes they have delayed effects. I hope that this is something that we do with this multi-format presentation, with a film installation, a performance, and research materials about and around the assassination of Yitzhak Rabin\" (Amos Gitai).\n\nIn 2017, Amos Gitai returns to the occupied territories for the first time since his 1982 documentary \"Field Diary\". \"WEST OF THE JORDAN RIVER\" describes the efforts of Israelis and Palestinians citizens, who try to overcome the consequences of the occupation. Gitai's documentary shows the human ties woven by the military, human rights activists, journalists, mourning mothers and even Jewish settlers. Faced with the failure of politics to solve the occupation, these men and women rise and act in the name of their civic consciousness. This human energy is a proposal for long overdue change. The film was premiered in Cannes International Film Festival 2017 \u2013 Directors' Fortnight.\n\n2018 is a year of intense activity for Amos Gitai, who presents at [[the Venice Film Festival]] \"A TRAMWAY IN JERUSALEM\", a light-hearted and dramatic fare on a tramway that connects several of Jerusalem's neighborhoods from East to West, bringing together a mosaic of people from different religious and ethnic backgrounds. \"The film describes an ironic, almost utopian situation in which most of the conflicts are contained and this beautiful city of Jerusalem charged with thousands of years of history facilitates people\u2019s way of living side by side.\" (Amos Gitai) \nCast: [[Mathieu Amalric]], [[Pippo Delbono]], [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Hanna Laszlo]], among 36 Israeli, Palestinian and European actors and actresses.\n\nThe film is preceded by Amos Gitai's \"[[A LETTER TO A FRIEND IN GAZA]]\" (2018, 34 mins, in Hebrew & Arabic). The film responds to the current crisis between Israel and Gaza. 2 Palestinians and 2 Israelis read texts inspired by [[Mahmoud Darwish]], [[Yizhar Smilansky]], [[Emile Habibi]] and [[Amira Hass]], as an homage to a famous letter written by [[Albert Camus]] in 1943, which gives its title to the film.\n\n===Novel adaptations===\nGitai created several novel adaptations. ''One day you'll understand'' (\"Plus tard tu comprendras\", 2008) is based on an autobiographical book by [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Cl\u00e9ment]], president of the Arte television channel and one of the leading figures of French culture, and tells the story of a French writer tracing the story of his Jewish mother ([[Jeanne Moreau]]) and her family during World War II.<ref>[[:fr:J\u00e9r\u00f4me Cl\u00e9ment]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n<ref>A. O. Scott. (30 October 2008).\n[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/31/movies/31unde.html In Search of Family History Despite the Threat of Pain]. [[The New York Times]]\n</ref>\n''[[Roses \u00e0 cr\u00e9dit]]'' (2010) is an adaptation of the novel by [[Elsa Triolet]] and takes a look at the materialist, post-war world of the French lower middle-class.<ref>http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2010/rosescredit#filmnote  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010073126/http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/tiff/2010/rosescredit#filmnote |date=10 October 2011 }}</ref>  The film was shot entirely in France. ''[[Tsili]]'' (2014) is inspired by the novel by [[Aharon Appelfeld]], and tells the story of the wandering of its heroine submerged in the nightmare of the war. Tsili, a young Jewish woman, gathers all the forces of intuition and vitality to survive in this desperate universe. \nstarring [[Sarah Adler]], Meshi Olinski, and [[Lea Koenig]].\n<ref>https://www.huffingtonpost.com/e-nina-rothe/best-of-venice-with-tsili_b_5815176.html</ref>\n\"I was inspired by what Aharon Appelfeld told Philip Roth :The reality of the Holocaust surpassed any imagination. If I remained true to the facts, no one would believe me. But the moment I chose a girl, a little older than I was at that time, I removed ''the story of my life'' from the mighty grip of memory and gave it over to the creative laboratory. There memory is not the only proprietor. There one needs a causal explanation, a thread to tie things together. The exceptional is permissible only if it is part of an overall structure and contributes to its understanding. \nWhen I wrote ''Tsili'' I was interested in the possibilities of naiveness in art. Can there be a naive modern art? It seemed to me that without the naivete still found among children and old people and, to some extent, in ourselves, the work of art would be flawed. I tried to correct that flaw.\" (Amos Gitai)\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Amos Gitai and Arthur Miller\".jpg|thumb|Amos Gitai and Arthur Miller]] -->\n\n===Exhibitions, publications and performances===\nGitai\u2019s work include film installations, stage work and books publications. Various publications and exhibitions took place, devoted to his parents Munio and Efratia: Traces at the Palais de Tokyo (Paris), the [[Bauhaus]] (Dessau, Germany), the art museum of the Ein Harod kibbutz (Israel), and Kib- butz Kfar Masaryk Dining Hall at the MoMA (New York, 2013). Retrospective and installation at the Museo nazionale del cinema in Turin.\nIn 2010 Gitai presents at The Od\u00e9on-Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de l\u2019Europe \"The War of the Sons of Light against the Sons of Darkness\", a work staged in the Boulbon quarry, at the Avignon Festival (July 2009). He publishes as well the letters of his mother Efratia (Efratia Gitai: Correspondence 1929\u20131994, Gallimard), which are read by Jeanne Moreau at the Od\u00e9on-Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de l\u2019Europe and on France Culture. In 2011 Gitai inaugurated the Munio Gitai Weinraub Architecture Museum in his father's old offices in Haifa.<ref>http://ropac.net/artist/amos-gitai</ref><ref>http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xhp9ae_traces-d-amos-gitai-au-palais-de-tokyo_creation</ref>\n\nAfter the premier of his film 'Rabin, the Last Day', Gitai continues his investigation into the assassination of the Israeli Prime Minister with an installation \u00ab Chronicle of an assassination foretold \u00bb presented at the MAXXI Museum (Rome),<ref>http://www.fondazionemaxxi.it/en/events/cronaca-di-un-assassinio-annunciato.html{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Bozar Museum (Brussels)<ref>http://www.bozar.be/fr/activities/112519-amos-gitai.html</ref> and the Fondation Lambert en Avignon.<ref>http://www.collectionlambert.fr/7/expositions/en-cours.html</ref> Ceramics, photographs, and video installations propose a new reading of the events that led to the assassination of the Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin on 4 November 1995, in Tel Aviv.<ref>https://www.ft.com/content/b63bb70e-484f-11e6-8d68-72e9211e86ab)</ref>\n\nThis installation also echoes a theatrical performance given in July 2016 in the Cour d'honneur of the Palais des papes at the Festival d'Avignon. In Yitzhak Rabin : chronique d\u2019un assassinat, Gitai uses the memories of Leah Rabin, the Prime Minister's widow, as a springboard. Four voices (two actresses, Hiam Abbass and Sarah Adler, and two musicians, Edna Stern (piano) and [[Sonia Wieder-Atherton]] (cello) create a recitative, \u201chalfway between lament and lullaby,\u201d to travel back through History and explore the incredible violence with which the nationalist forces fought the peace project, tearing Israel apart. Four voices caught \u201clike in an echo chamber,\u201d between image-documents and excerpts from classic and contemporary literature.\n\nIn July 2016, a 540-page book on Amos Gitai was published by Galerie Enrico Navarra and S\u00e9bastien Moreu. The book includes more than 250 reproductions from movies and research, but also family archives and creations by Amos Gitai and 7 conversations between Gitai and : [[Hans-Ulrich Obrist]], [[Guy Amsellem]], [[Arthur Miller]], [[Hou Hanru]], [[Annette Michelson]], [[Richard Ingersoll]], [[Elisabeth Lebovici]] & [[Stephan Levine]]), two poems (Mount Carmel and Lullaby to My Father) and a poetic essay on the Golem.\n<ref>[[\u00c9lisabeth Lebovici]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\nOn 8 October 2018, the [[Philharmonie de Paris]] presents \"[[Yitzhak Rabin Chronicle of an Assassination]]\" created in Avignon in 2016, with [[Barbara Hendricks]], [[Yael Abecassis]], [[Sarah Adler]], [[Gavriel Lipkind]] (cello), [[Edna Stern]] (piano).\n\n==Personal life==\nGitai was born in Haifa and divides his time today between Paris and Haifa.\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Golem l'esprit de l'exil - Shemesh and Schygulla - 1992.jpg|thumbnail|right|250px|[[Ophrah Shemesh]] and [[Hanna Schygulla]] in ''[[Golem, the Spirit of the Exile]]'', 1991]]\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''My Mother at the Seashore'' (1973)\n* ''Bayit'' (1980)\n* ''Yoman Sadeh'' (1982)\n* ''Bangkok-Bahrein'' (1983) \n* ''Ananas'' (1984)\n* ''[[Esther (1986 film)|Esther]]'' (1986)\n* ''Brand New Day''\n* ''[[Berlin-Jerusalem]]'' (1989)\n* ''{{ill|Birth of a Golem|fr|Naissance d'un Golem}}'' (1991)\n* ''[[Golem, the Spirit of the Exile]]'' (1992)\n* ''{{ill|Zihron Devarim|fr|Devarim (film)}}'' (1995)\n* ''Zirat Ha'Rezach'' (1996)\n* ''[[Metamorphosis of a Melody]]'' (1996)\n* ''War and Peace in Vesoul'' (1997)\n* ''{{ill|A House in Jerusalem|it}}'' (1998)\n* ''Orange'' (1998)\n* ''Zion, Auto-Emancipation'' (1998)\n* ''{{ill|Yom Yom|fr}}'' (1998)\n* ''[[Kadosh]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Kippur]]'' (2000)\n* ''{{ill|Eden (2001 film)|lt=Eden|fr|Eden (film, 2001)}}'' (2001)\n* ''[[Kedma (film)|Kedma]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[11'09\"01 September 11]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Alila]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Promised Land (2004 film)|Promised Land]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Free Zone (film)|Free Zone]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Disengagement (film)|Disengagement]]'' (2007)\n* ''{{ill|One day you'll understand|fr|Plus tard tu comprendras}}'' (2008)\n* ''{{ill|Carmel (film 2009)|it|lt=Carmel}}'' (2009)\n* ''The War of the Sons of Light Against the Sons of Darkness'' (2009)\n* ''{{lang|fr|[[Roses \u00e0 cr\u00e9dit]]}}'' (2010)\n* ''[[Lullaby to My Father]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Ana Arabia]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Words With Gods]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Tsili]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Rabin, the Last Day]]'' (2015)\n* ''West of the Jordan River'' (2017)\n* ''{{ill|A Tramway in Jerusalem|fr|Un tramway \u00e0 J\u00e9rusalem}}'' (2018)\n* ''Letter to A Friend in Gaza'' (2018)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Exhibitions, performances==\n* The Law Of The Pursuer. An Essay Exhibition, [http://savvy-contemporary.com SAVVY Contemporary] Berlin, Germany, February - March 2017<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://savvy-contemporary.com/index.php/exhibitions/the-law-of-the-pursuer/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209052540/http://savvy-contemporary.com/index.php/exhibitions/the-law-of-the-pursuer |archive-date=9 February 2017 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Chronique d'un assassinat, theater performance, 72nd festival d'Avignon, France, July 2016<ref>http://www.festival-avignon.com/fr/.html</ref>\n* Chronique d'un assassinat annonc\u00e9 - Exhibition in Fondation Lambert in Avignon, France, 3 July \u2013 6 November 2016<ref>/http://www.collectionlambert.fr/evenement/217/l-ete-a-la-collection-lambert.html</ref>\n* Exhibition at the galerie Thaddeus Ropac, Salzburg, Austria, 2015<ref>http://ropac.net/selected_works/amos-gitai</ref>\n* Ways/Strade, Palazzo Reale, Milan, 2014-2015\n* Amos Gitai biografias, Mus\u00e9e Reina Sofia, 2014 (commissaires : Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Chevrier, Elia Pijollet).\n* Amos Gitai Architecte de la m\u00e9moire, Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que fran\u00e7aise (Paris), Mus\u00e9e de l\u2019\u00c9lys\u00e9e (Lausanne), Galerie des Beaux Arts (Bruxelles), 2014 (commissaire : Matthieu Orl\u00e9an)\n* Before and After, galerie Thaddeus Ropac, Paris Pantin, 2014 et Villa Kast, Salzbourg, 2015\n* Disaster / The End of Days (exposition collective), galerie Thaddeus Ropac, Paris, 2013\n* Architecture de la m\u00e9moire, installation, \u00c9glise des Fr\u00e8res pr\u00eacheurs, rencontres photographiques d\u2019Arles, 2012<ref>http://www.rencontres-arles.com/C.aspx?VP3=CMS3&VF=ARL_791.html</ref>\n* ''Correspondence, Efrati Gitai \u2013 Letters'', [[Ein Harod#Museums|Museum of Art, Ein Harod]],  Israel, 2011\n* ''Traces - Munio Gitai \u2013 Weinraub'', Museum of Art, Ein Harod,  Israel, 2011\n* ''Traces'', an installation at the [[Palais de Tokyo]], Paris, 2011<ref>{{cite web|last=Anderman |first=Nirit |url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/amos-gitai-exhibit-on-father-opens-in-paris-1.341700 |title=Amos Gitai exhibit on father opens in Paris - Haaretz Daily Newspaper &#124; Israel News |publisher=Haaretz.com |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105065824/http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/amos-gitai-exhibit-on-father-opens-in-paris-1.341700|archivedate=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Lullaby for my father'', a video presentation in Kibbutz Kfar Masaryk, Israel, 2010\n* ''The War of the Sons of Light Against the Sons of Darkness'', (with ''[[Jeanne Moreau]]''), [[Festival d'Avignon]], France, 2009\n* ''Traces'' - Evento, [[Bordeaux]], 2009\n* ''Munio Weinraub / Amos Gitai - Architecture und Film in Israel'', Pinakothek der Moderne, ArchitekturMuseum, Munich, 2008-2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architekturmuseum.de/en/ausstellungen/detail.php?which=164 |title=Architekturmuseum der TU M\u00fcnchen [Exhibitions&#93; |publisher=Architekturmuseum.de |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313085852/http://www.architekturmuseum.de/en/ausstellungen/detail.php?which=164|archivedate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n* Munio Weinraub / Amos Gitai - Architecture and Film in Israel, Tel Aviv Museum, [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]] 2008-2009\n* ''Amos Gitai: Non-Fiction'', [[MoMA]] (Museum of Modern Art) New York, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/638 |title=MoMA &#124; MoMA Presents: Amos Gitai's News from Home/News from House |publisher=Google.co.il |date= |accessdate=1 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303193558/https://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/638|archivedate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Exhibition in memory of his father Munia Gitai \u2013 Weinraub'' - Amos Gitai, Olivier Cinqualbre and Lionel Richard, [[Centre Pompidou]], Paris 2006\n* ''Public Housing'' - long video presentation screens, Ein Harod Museum, Herzliya Museum, Saitama Museum of Modern Art, [[Saitama, Saitama|Saitama]], Japan, 2000\n* ''Open Shen Zen'' - Performance, [[Helena Rubinstein#Divorce and remarriage|Helena Rubinstein Pavilion]], Tel - Aviv 1998\n* ''Exhibition in memory to his father - Munio Gitai \u2013 Weinraub'', [[Israel Museum|Jerusalem Museum]], Israel, 1994\n\n==Books==\n* ''Efratia Gitai \u2013 letters'', Yediot books, Israel, 2011\n* ''Efratia Gitai, {{lang|fr|Correspondence}} (1929\u20131994)''', Gallimard, Paris, 2010\n* ''Gen\u00e8ses'', ''Jean-Michel Frodon, Amos Gitai, Marie-Jos\u00e9 Sanselme'', Gallimard, Paris, 2009\n* ''Monte Carmelo'', Amos Gitai, Bompiani, Milano, 2004\n* ''[[Parcours]]'', Amos Gitai, Centre Pompidou, Paris, 2003\n* ''Mont Carmel'', Amos Gitai, Gallimard, 2003\n* ''Munio Gitai Weinraub, Bauhaus architect in Israel'', Richard Ingersoll, Electa, Milano, 1994\n* ''[[The War of the Sons of Light Against the Sons of Darkness]]'', Amos Gitai,  Mazzotta, Milano, 1993\n\n==Books on Amos Gitai's work==\n* ''Amos Gitai'', Galerie Enrico Navarra, \u00e9ditions S\u00e9bastien Moreu, Paris, 2016\n* ''Cinema di Amos Gitai: Frontiere e territori (Il)'', Serge Toubiana, Bruno Mondadori, Torino, 2006\n* ''Amos Gitai: News from Home'', Walther K\u00f6nig, K\u00f6ln, 2006\n* ''The Cinema of Amos Gitai'',''Serge Toubiana'', Baptiste Pi\u00e9gay, Lincoln Center / Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, Paris, 2005\n* ''Amos Gitai'', ''Serge Toubiana'', Mostra internacional de cinema / Cosac Naify, S\u00e3o Paulo, 2004\n* ''Exilios y territories, el cine de Amos Gitai'', Serge Toubiana, Baptiste Pi\u00e9gay, Semana Internacional de Cine, Valladolid, 2004\n* ''Exils et territoires: le cin\u00e9ma d'Amos Gitai'', Serge Toubiana, Baptiste Pi\u00e9gay, Arte Editions / Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, Paris, 2003\n* ''Amos Gitai, Cinema, Politics, Aesthetics'', Irma Klein, KM, Tel Aviv, 2003\n* ''Amos Gitai, Cinema forza di pace'', Edited by Daniela Turco, Le Mani, Genova, 2002\n* ''The Films of Amos Gitai'', a Montage, Edited by Paul Willemen, BFI Publishing, London, 1993\n* ''Amos Gitai'', Edited by Alberto Farassino, Mostra Internazionale Riminicinema, Rimini, 1989\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nAmos Gitai: Exile and Atonement, ''Ray Privett'', Cinema Purgatorio, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Amos Gitai}}\n* [http://www.amosgitai.com/ Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|321159}}\n* [http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/188299/Amos_Gitai Amos Gitai], Hollywood.com\n{{Amos Gitai}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gitai, Amos}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Haifa]]\n[[Category:Israeli filmmakers]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:Israeli screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Israeli architects]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli film directors]]\n[[Category:Roberto Rossellini Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of the Yom Kippur War]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley College of Environmental Design alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Taliadvr